otnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 101\n| population_total                = 1,470,755{{efn|The figure corresponds to the expanded city limits. According to the [[2011 Indian census|2011 census]], the pre-expanded city covering an area of {{convert|51.82|km2|mi2}} had a population of 1,017,865.<ref name=\"census2011\">{{cite web |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/3322_PART_B_DCHB_MADURAI.pdf |title=Madurai District census handbook |publisher=Government of India |access-date=29 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803153908/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/3322_PART_B_DCHB_MADURAI.pdf |archivedate=3 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref>{{cite web |title=Socio-Economic Resources Profiling |url=http://www.maduraicorporation.co.in/socio-economis-resource-profiling.html |publisher=Madurai Corporation |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_metro                = 1,465,625\n| population_metro_footnotes      =  \n| population_rank                 = 3\n| population_demonym              = Maduraikaran\n| demographics_type1              = Language\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 625 xxx\n| area_code                       = [[Telephone numbers in India#Fixed .28landline.29 numbers|0452]]\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = TN-58 (South), TN-59 (North) and TN-64(Central)\n| website                         = {{URL|maduraicorporation.co.in}}\n| leader_title2                   = Commissioner of Police\n| leader_name2                    = S. Davidson's Devasirvatham [[Indian Police Service|IPS]]\n| area_metro_footnotes            = \n| demographics1_info1             = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n}}\n\n'''Madurai''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u00e6|dj|\u028a|r|a\u026a}} {{respell|MAD|yuu|ry}},<ref>{{Cite Oxford\u00a0Dictionaries|Madurai|accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Collins\">{{cite web|url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/madurai|title=Madurai|work=[[Collins English Dictionary]]|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref> <small>also</small> {{IPAc-en|US|\u02cc|m|\u0251\u02d0|d|\u0259|\u02c8|r|a\u026a}} {{respell|MAH|d\u0259|RY}}<ref name=\"Collins\"/><ref>{{Cite American Heritage Dictionary|Madurai|accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Merriam-Webster|Madurai|accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref>) is a major city in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Tamil Nadu]]. It is the cultural capital of [[Tamil Nadu]] and the administrative headquarters of [[Madurai District]], the third largest city in [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[List of cities in India by population|44th most populated city]] in India.{{sfn|Tamil N\u0101du \u2013 City Population \u2013 Cities, Towns & Provinces \u2013 Statistics & Map|2011}} Located on the banks of [[River Vaigai]], Madurai has been a major settlement for two millennia.\n\nMadurai is closely associated with the [[Tamil language]], and the third [[Tamil Sangam]], a major congregation of Tamil scholars said to have been held in the city. The [[recorded history]] of the city goes back to the 3rd century BCE, being mentioned by [[Megasthenes]], the Greek ambassador to the [[Maurya empire]], and [[Kautilya]], a minister of the Mauryan emperor [[Chandragupta Maurya]]. Signs of human settlements and Roman trade links dating back to 300 BC are evident from excavations by [[Archeological Survey of India]] in Manalur.{{sfn|''The Times of India''|13 October 2015}}{{sfn|''The Times of India''|12 October 2015}}{{sfn|''The Hindu''|12 October 2015}} The city is believed to be of significant antiquity and has been ruled, at different times, by the [[Pandyan Kingdom|Pandyas]], [[Cholas]], [[Madurai Sultanate]], [[Vijayanagar Empire]], [[Madurai Nayaks]], [[Nawab of the Carnatic|Carnatic kingdom]], and the [[British East India Company]] [[British Raj]].\n\nThe city has a number of historical monuments, with the [[Meenakshi Temple]] and the [[Tirumalai Nayak Palace]] being the most prominent. Madurai is an important industrial and educational hub in South Tamil Nadu. The city is home to various automobile, [[rubber]], chemical and [[granite]] manufacturing industries.{{sfn|''The Hindu''|25 October 2007}}\n\nMadurai has important government educational institutes such as the [[Madurai Medical College]], Homeopathic Medical College,{{sfn|List of Colleges in Madurai}} [[Government Law College, Madurai|Madurai Law College]], Agricultural College and Research Institute. Madurai city is administered by [[Madurai Municipal Corporation|a municipal corporation]] established in 1971 as per the Municipal Corporation Act. The city covers an area of 147.97&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> and had a population of 1,470,755 in 2011.{{sfn|Madurai 2011 census data}} The city is also the seat of a bench of the [[Madras High Court]]. The Madurai Bench has been functioning since 2004.\n\n==Etymology==\nAccording to  [[Iravatham Mahadevan]], a 2nd-century BCE [[Tamil-Brahmi]] inscription refers to the city as ''matiray'', an Old Tamil word meaning a \"walled city\".{{sfn|Mahadevan}}<ref>{{cite book |last=Mahadevan|first=Iravatham |date=3 Oct 2003|title=Early Tamil Epigraphy from the Earliest Times to the Sixth Century A.D. |url= |location= |publisher=Harvard University Press|page= |isbn=0674012275|author-link=}}</ref>\n\nMadurai is one of the many temple towns in the state which is named after the groves, clusters or forests dominated by a particular variety of a tree or shrub and the same variety of tree or shrub sheltering the presiding deity. The region is believed to have been covered with Kadamba forest and hence called Kadambavanam.{{sfn|Reddy| 2013| p= 10}} The city is referred by various names including \"Madurai\", \"Koodal\",  \"Malligai Maanagar\", \"Naanmadakoodal\" and \"Thirualavai\". The word ''Madurai'' may be derived from Madhura (sweetness) arising out of the divine nectar showered on the city by the Hindu god [[Shiva|Siva]] from his matted hair.{{sfn|Harman| 1992| pp= 30\u201336}}  Another theory is that ''Madurai'' is the derivative of the word ''Marutham'', which refers to the type of landscape of the [[Sangam Age|Sangam age]]. A town in the neighbouring [[Dindigul district]] is called Vada Madurai (''North Madurai'') and another in [[Sivagangai district]] is called [[Manamadurai]]. The different names by which the city has been referred to historically are listed in the 7th-century poem ''Thiruvilayaadal puraanam'' written by Paranjothi Munivar.{{sfn|Harman| 1992| pp= 30\u201336}}{{sfn|Reynolds|Bardwell| 1987| pp= 12\u201325}}\n\n''Koodal'' means an assembly or congregation of scholarly people, referring to the three Tamil Sangams held at Madurai. Naanmadakoodal, meaning the junction of four towers, refers to the four major temples for which Madurai was known for.{{sfn|Harman| 1992| pp= 30\u201336}} ''[[Thevaram (Tamil Shaivaite Hymns)|Tevaram]]'', the 7th- or 8th-century Tamil compositions on Shiva by the three prominent [[Nayanars]] (''[[Saivites]]''), namely [[Appar]],{{sfn|Thirunavukkarasar|2004| pp= 44\u201347}} [[Sundarar]] and Thirugnanasambandar,{{sfn|Campantar Tirumurai 1|2004| p= 61}}{{sfn|Campantar Tirumurai 3|2004| pp= 56\u201358}} address the city as ''Thirualavai''.{{sfn|Harman| 1992| pp= 30\u201336}}{{sfn|Prentiss| 1999| p= 43}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Martin Madurai 1860.jpg|thumb|left|Hand coloured antique wood engraving drawn by W. Purser (1858) shows Madurai city as seen from the north bank of the [[Vaigai river]]|alt=view of city having temple towers seen through two trees]]\n\nMadurai has been inhabited since at least the 3rd century BCE.{{sfn|Zvelebil|1992|p=27}} [[Megasthenes]] may have visited Madurai during the 3rd century BCE, with the city referred as \"Methora\" in his accounts.{{sfn|Harman| 1992| pp= 30\u201336}} The view is contested by some scholars who believe \"Methora\" refers to the north Indian city of [[Mathura]], as it was a large and established city in the [[Mauryan Dynasty|Mauryan Empire]].{{sfn|Quintanilla|2007|p=2}} Madurai is also mentioned in [[Kautilya]]'s (370\u2013283 BCE){{sfn|Agarwal | 2008| p= 17}} ''[[Arthashastra]]''.{{sfn|Harman| 1992| pp= 30\u201336}} [[Sangam literature]] like ''[[Maturaikk\u0101\u00f1ci]]'' records the importance of Madurai as a capital city of the Pandyan dynasty.{{sfn|Mangudi Marudanar|2004}}{{sfn|Gopal|1990|p=181}} Madurai is mentioned in the works of [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] historians [[Pliny the Younger]] (61&nbsp;\u2013 c. 112 CE), [[Ptolemy]] (c. 90&nbsp;\u2013 c. CE 168), those of the [[Greeks|Greek]] geographer [[Strabo]] (64/63 BCE&nbsp;\u2013 c. 24 CE),{{sfn|Bandopadhyay| 2010|pp= 93\u201396}} and also in [[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea]].{{sfn|Reynolds|Bardwell| 1987| pp= 12\u201325}}\n\n[[File:Pandya Kingdom (south India).png|right|thumb|Pandyan dynasty Map at its greatest extent]]\n[[File:Coin of Jalaluddin Ahsan Khan.jpg|right|thumb|Coin of [[Jalaluddin Ahsan Khan]], first ruler of the [[Madurai Sultanate|Sultanate of Madurai]], 1335\u20131339 CE|alt=historic metal coin used for transaction]]\nAfter the Sangam age, most of present-day Tamil Nadu, including Madurai, came under the rule of the [[Kalabhra dynasty]], which was ousted by the [[Pandya]]s around 590 CE.{{sfn|Dalal|1997|p=128}}{{sfn|Kersenboom Story|1987|p=16}} The Pandyas were ousted from Madurai by the [[Chola dynasty]] during the early 9th century.{{sfn|Salma Ahmed|2011|p=26}} The city remained under the control of the Cholas until the early 13th century, when the second Pandyan empire was established with Madurai as its capital.{{sfn|Salma Ahmed|2011|p=26}} After the death of [[Maravarman Kulasekara Pandyan I|Kulasekara Pandian]] (1268\u20131308 CE), Madurai came under the rule of the [[Tughlaq dynasty|Delhi Sultanate]].{{sfn|Salma Ahmed|2011|p=26}} The [[Madurai Sultanate]] then seceded from Delhi and functioned as an independent kingdom until its gradual annexation by the [[Vijayanagar Empire]] in 1378 CE.{{sfn|V. |1995| p= 115}} Madurai became independent from Vijayanagar in 1559 CE under the [[Madurai Nayak Dynasty|Nayaks]].{{sfn|V. |1995| p= 115}} Nayak rule ended in 1736 CE and Madurai was repeatedly captured several times by [[Chanda Sahib]] (1740&nbsp;\u2013 1754 CE), [[Nawab of the Carnatic|Arcot Nawab]] and [[Muhammed Yusuf Khan]] (1725&nbsp;\u2013 1764 CE) in the middle of 18th century.{{sfn|Harman| 1992| pp= 30\u201336}}\n\nIn 1801, Madurai came under the direct control of the [[British East India Company]] and was annexed to the [[Madras Presidency]].{{sfn|Markovits|2004|p=253}}{{sfn|B.S.|S.|C.|2011|p=582}} The British government made donations to the [[Meenakshi temple]] and participated in the Hindu festivals during the early part of their rule.{{sfn|King| 2005| pp=73\u201375}} The city evolved as a political and industrial complex through the 19th and 20th centuries to become a district headquarters of a larger Madurai district.{{sfn|King| 2005| pp=73\u201375}} In 1837, the fortifications around the temple were demolished by the British.{{sfn|Reynolds|Bardwell| 1987| p= 18}} The moat was drained and the debris was used to construct new streets&nbsp;\u2013 Veli, Marat and Perumaal Mesthiri streets.{{sfn|Narasaiah| 2009| p= 85}}  The city was constituted as a municipality in 1866 CE.{{sfn|Madurai Corporation \u2013 citizen charter}} The British government faced initial hiccups during the earlier period of the establishment of municipality in land ceiling and tax collection in Madurai and Dindigul districts under the direct administration of the officers of the government.{{sfn|Imperial gazetteer of India: Provincial series, Volume 18|1908| pp= 229\u2013230}} The city, along with the district, was resurveyed between 1880 and 1885 CE and subsequently, five municipalities were constituted in the two districts and six taluk boards were set up for local administration.{{sfn|Imperial gazetteer of India: Provincial series, Volume 18|1908| pp= 229\u2013230}} Police stations were established in Madurai city, housing the headquarters of the District Superintendent.{{sfn|Imperial gazetteer of India: Provincial series, Volume 18|1908| pp= 229\u2013230}} Under the British Madurai prospered.\n\nIt was in Madurai, in 1921, that [[Mahatma Gandhi]], pre-eminent leader of [[Indian nationalism]] in British-ruled India, first adopted the loin cloth as his mode of dress after seeing agricultural labourers wearing it.{{sfn|Gandhi Memorial Museum, Madurai}} Leaders of the independence movement in Madurai included [[N.M.R. Subbaraman]],{{sfn|Kamat Research Database, Biography: N.M.R.Subbaraman}}{{sfn|David Arnold| 1977| p= 128}} [[Karumuttu Thiagarajan Chettiar]] and Mohammad Ismail Sahib.{{sfn|More J. B. P| 1977| p= 106}} The Temple Entry Authorization and Indemnity Act passed by the government of [[Madras Presidency]]  under [[C. Rajagopalachari]] in 1939 removed restrictions prohibiting [[Shanars]] and [[Dalits]] from entering Hindu temples. The temple entry movement was first led in Madurai Meenakshi temple by independence activist [[A. Vaidyanatha Iyer]] in 1939.{{sfn|Press Information Bureau archives, Government of India}}{{sfn|''The Hindu''|26 February 2011}}\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Madurai Map OSM002.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Map of Madurai showing centre of the city and some important landmarks|alt=map of city showing main streets in the centre of a city]]\n\nMadurai is built around the Meenakshi Amman Temple, which acted as the geographic and ritual centre of the ancient city of Madurai.{{sfn|King| 2005| p= 72}} The city is divided into a number of concentric quadrangular streets around the temple.{{sfn|King| 2005| p= 72}} [[Vishwanatha Nayak]] (1529\u201364 CE), the first Madurai Nayak king, redesigned the city in accordance with the principles laid out by ''[[Shilpa Shastras]]'' (Sanskrit: ''{{IAST|\u015bilpa \u015b\u0101stra}}'', also anglicised as ''silpa sastra'' meaning rules of architecture) related to urban planning. These squares retain their traditional names of Aadi, Chittirai, Avani-moola and Masi streets, corresponding to the Tamil month names and also to the festivals associated.{{sfn|King| 2005| p= 72}} The temple ''[[prakaram]]s'' (outer precincts of a temple) and streets accommodate an elaborate festival calendar in which dramatic processions circumambulate the shrines at varying distances from the centre. The temple chariots used in processions are progressively larger in size based on the size of the concentric streets.{{sfn|Selby|Peterson| 2008| p= 149}} Ancient Tamil classics record the temple as the centre of the city and the surrounding streets appearing liken a lotus and its petals.{{sfn|Reynolds|Bardwell| 1987| pp= 12\u201325}} The city's axes were aligned with the four quarters of the compass, and the four gateways of the temple provided access to it.{{sfn|King| 2005| p= 73}} The wealthy and higher echelons of the society were placed in streets close to the temple, while the poorest were placed in the fringe streets.{{sfn|King| 2005| p= 73}} With the advent of British rule during the 19th century, Madurai became the headquarters of a large colonial political complex and an industrial town; with urbanisation, the social hierarchical classes became unified.{{sfn|King| 2005| p=l 73}}\n\n==Geography and climate==\n[[File:Vaigai-MDU.jpg|thumb|350px|left|Vaigai river in Madurai|alt=river with water flowing amidst weeds]]\n\n{{climate chart\n|Madurai\n|20.6|32.8|8.5\n|21.5|34.3|11.0\n|23.4|36.0|18.3\n|25.6|37.2|60.1\n|26.3|37.9|80.6\n|26.2|38.2|34.3\n|25.9|36.5|56.9\n|25.5|36.2|93.9\n|24.6|35.1|121.5\n|23.7|33.1|185.8\n|22.7|31.6|147.2\n|21.3|30.0|51.3\n| float = right\n}}\n\nAs typical with Tamil Nadu, Madurai has a dry-summer [[tropical savannah climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]: '''As''').\n\nMadurai is located at {{Coord|9.93|N|78.12|E}}.{{sfn|Maps, Weather, and Airports for Madurai, India}} It has an average elevation of 101 metres. The city of Madurai lies on the flat and fertile plain of the river [[Vaigai]], which runs in the northwest\u2013southeast direction through the city, dividing it into two almost equal halves.{{sfn|Madurai Corporation \u2013 General information}} The Sirumalai and Nagamalai hills lie to the north and west of Madurai.{{sfn|Imperial Gazetter of India, Volume 16|1908| p= 404}} The land in and around Madurai is utilised largely for agricultural activity, which is fostered by the [[Periyar Dam]].{{sfn|Imperial Gazetter of India, Volume 16|1908| p= 404}} Madurai lies southeast of the western ghats, and the surrounding region occupies the plains of South India and contains several mountain spurs.{{sfn|Pletcher|2011| p= 192}} The soil type in central Madurai is predominantly clay loam, while red loam and black cotton types are widely prevalent in the outer fringes of the city.{{sfn|Department of Agriculture}} Paddy is the major crop, followed by pulses, millet, oil seed, cotton and sugarcane.{{sfn|Department of Agriculture}}\n\nThe municipal corporation of Madurai has an area of 147.97&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.{{sfn|Madurai Corporation \u2013 General information}}{{sfn|TN Govt GO #220}} Madurai is hot and dry for eight months of the year.{{sfn|Annesley|1841|p=68}} Cold winds are experienced during February and March as in the neighbouring [[Dindigul]].{{sfn|Annesley|1841|p=68}} The hottest months are from March to July.{{sfn|Annesley|1841|p=68}} The city experiences a moderate climate from August to October, tempered by heavy rain and thundershowers, and a slightly cooler climate from November to February.{{sfn|Annesley|1841|p=68}} Fog and dew are rare, occurring only during the winter season.{{sfn|Annesley|1841|p=68}} Being equidistant from mountains and the sea, it experiences similar monsoon pattern with [[Northeast monsoon]] and [[Southwest monsoon]], with the former providing more rain during October to December.{{sfn|Annesley|1841|p=68}} The average annual rainfall for the Madurai district is about 85.76&nbsp;cm.{{sfn|Water year \u2013 District ground water brochure, Madurai district}} Mostly Dry weather prevails throughout the year.\n\nTemperatures during summer generally reach a maximum of 42&nbsp;\u00b0C and a minimum of 26.3&nbsp;\u00b0C, although temperatures up to 43&nbsp;\u00b0C are not uncommon.{{sfn|''The Hindu''|21 April 2010}} Winter temperatures range between 29.6&nbsp;\u00b0C and 18&nbsp;\u00b0C. A study based on the data available with the Indian Meteorological Department on Madurai over a period of 62 years indicate rising trend in atmospheric temperature over Madurai city, attributed to urbanisation, growth of vehicles and industrial activity.{{sfn|''The Hindu''|21 April 2010}} The maximum temperature of 42&nbsp;\u00b0C for the decade of 2001 \u2013 2010 was recorded in 2004 and in 2010.{{sfn|''The Hindu''|21 April 2010}}\n\n{{Weather box|location = Madurai, India (1981\u20132010)\n| single line  = yes\n| metric first = yes\n| Jan record high C = 39.1\n| Feb record high C = 38.5\n| Mar record high C = 41.7\n| Apr record high C = 42.1\n| May record high C = 44.5\n| Jun record high C = 42.2\n| Jul record high C = 40.6\n| Aug record high C = 40.0\n| Sep record high C = 39.8\n| Oct record high C = 40.0\n| Nov record high C = 38.0\n| Dec record high C = 37.0\n| year record high C = 44.5\n| Jan high C = 30.8\n| Feb high C = 33.3\n| Mar high C = 36.0\n| Apr high C = 37.2\n| May high C = 37.9\n| Jun high C = 37.2\n| Jul high C = 36.5\n| Aug high C = 36.2\n| Sep high C = 35.1\n| Oct high C = 33.1\n| Nov high C = 30.6\n| Dec high C = 30.0\n| year high C = 34