]]\n**Play-Off Winners: [[2007\u201308 Football League Two|2007\u201308]]\n*Division Three (North) Challenge Cup\n**Winners: [[1934\u201335 in English football|1934\u201335]]\n*[[Football League Trophy]]\n**Runners Up: [[1991-92 Football League Trophy|1991\u201392]], [[1992-93 Football League Trophy|1992\u201393]]\n\n===Other competitions===\n*[[National League North]] \u2013 Tier 6\n**Champions: [[2018\u201319 National League|2018\u201319]]\n*[[Lancashire League (football)|Lancashire League]]\n**Champions: 1899\u20131900\n*[[Lancashire Combination]]\n**Champions: 1904\u201305\n*[[Manchester Senior Cup]]\n**Winners: 1897\u201398, 1898\u201399, 1914\u201315, 1922\u201323\n*Cheshire Medal Winners:\n**1922\u201323, 1924\u201325, 1928\u201329, 1929\u201330, 1930\u201331\n*Cheshire Bowl Winners:\n**1933\u201334, 1948\u201349, 1952\u201353, 1955\u201356, 1956\u201357,1958\u201359, 1960\u201361, 1962\u201363\n*Cheshire Friendly Trophy Winners:\n**1965\u201366, 1966\u201367\n*[[Cheshire Premier Cup]]\n**Winners: 1969\u201370, 1970\u201371, 2010\u201311\n*[[Cheshire Senior Cup]]\n**Winners: 1905\u201306, 1946\u201347, 1948\u201349, 1965\u201366, 2015\u201316\n\n==Club records and statistics==\n\n===Team records===\n*Biggest home win: 13\u20130 vs. [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]], 6 January 1934, also a [[Football League]] record<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Football League Matches: Arsenal Only Draw, Record Scoring by Stockport|work=The Manchester Guardian|date=8 January 1934|page=3}}</ref>\n*Biggest home defeat: 0\u20136, twice, most recently 24 April 2010 vs. [[Huddersfield Town F.C|Huddersfield Town]]<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Biggest away win: 7\u20131 at [[Bradford City F.C.|Bradford City]], 18 September 1965<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\"Stockport County : Records\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Biggest away defeat: 0\u20139, vs. [[Everton F.C.|Everton Reserves]], 9 December 1893<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Consecutive wins: 9, [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]]<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\"Stockport County : Records\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Consecutive away wins: 8, [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]]<ref name=\"Programmes\"/><ref name=\"Stockport boss has a young vision\">{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/7305219.stm | title=Stockport boss has a young vision| publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 March 2008|last=Oliver|first=Pete| accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref>\n*Consecutive wins without conceding a goal: 9, [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]], also a [[Football League]] record<ref name=\"Programmes\"/><ref name=\"Stockport boss has a young vision\" /><ref name=\"FL record\">{{cite news |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/sport/story/0,,2026082,00.html |title=Leeds deeper in gloom as Nicholls says he wants away |accessdate=15 April 2012 |date=4 March 2007|last=Tomas|first=Jason|location=London|work=The Observer}}</ref>\n*Consecutive defeats: 12, [[2009\u201310 in English football|2009\u201310]]<ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Consecutive games scored in: 30, [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]]<ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Consecutive League games scored in: 26, [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]]<ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Highest attendance: 27,833 vs. [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], FA Cup Fifth Round, 11 February 1950<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Highest league attendance: 24,473 vs. [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]], Third Division North, 20 October 1951\n*Highest attendance (all-seated): 10,273 vs. Leeds United, 28 December 2008<ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Lowest attendance: 812 vs. Barrow, 19 November 2013<ref name=\"FA Trophy replay: Stockport County 2 Barrow 3\">{{cite news |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/fa-trophy-replay-stockport-county-6323773 |title=FA Trophy replay: Stockport County 2 Barrow 3|accessdate=16 September 2014 |date=20 November 2013|last=Browne|first=Gavin|location=Manchester|work=Manchester Evening News}}</ref>\n*Longest match: 3 hours 23 minutes vs. [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]], 30 March 1946, also a world record<ref name=\"Programmes\"/><ref name=\"When extra time had no end: how one match lasted 3hrs and 23mins\" />\n*Lowest number of paying spectators: 13 vs. [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] (at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]], 7 May 1921) also a [[Football League]] record*.<ref name=\"Programmes\"/><ref name=\"DID YOU KNOW.....PITCHES and what they have had to put up with........\">{{cite news |url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/DYK/DYK23-Pitches.htm#They%20say%20that%20groundsmen%20would |title=DID YOU KNOW.....PITCHES and what they have had to put up with........|publisher=footballsite.co.uk |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n<sup>*It is estimated that between 1,000 and 2,000 people actually attended the match; [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] had played immediately beforehand, and some spectators for that match had stayed on to watch the Stockport match for free. However, only 13 people paid at the gate to watch the Stockport match by itself.</sup>\n\n===Player records===\n*Most goals (season): 46 League by Alf Lythgoe, [[1933\u201334 in English football|1933\u201334]]<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Most goals (career): 132 by [[Jack Connor (footballer born 1919)|Jack Connor]] (1951\u20131956)<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Fastest League Goal (Starting XI): 13 seconds, [[Dominic Blizzard]] vs. [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]] 31 January 2009<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Fastest League Goal (Substitute): 21 seconds, Bohan Dixon vs. [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]]  6 January 2018<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Most appearances (career): 555 Andy Thorpe (1978\u20131986, 1988\u20131992)<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Most international appearances (caps) \u2013 9 [[Jarkko Wiss]], Finland (2000\u20132002)<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Youngest player: [[Paul Turnbull]], aged 16 years 97 days v [[Wrexham F.C.|Wrexham]], 30 April 2005<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Oldest player: Alec Herd, aged 47 years 40 days vs. [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], 25 December 1951<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Most consecutive clean sheets: 9 by [[Wayne Hennessey]], [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]], coinciding with league record for consecutive wins<ref name=\"FL record\" />\n\n===League pyramid statistics===\n''As of season 2019\u201320''<ref name=\"Stockport County datafile\">{{cite news |url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1fxPedcqk5r0Ks_LCvN62YNaagn9rGNKPmdh8kBQsq9k/edit#gid=0|title=Stockport County datafile |accessdate=30 August 2015 |publisher=Google Documents}}</ref>\n*Seasons spent at Level 1 of the [[English football league system|football league system]]: 0\n*Seasons spent at Level 2 of the football league system: 26\n*Seasons spent at Level 3 of the football league system: 40\n*Seasons spent at Level 4 of the football league system: 33\n*Seasons spent at Level 5 of the football league system: 3\n*Seasons spent at Level 6 of the football league system: 6\n\n===Nine game winning run===\nStockport County hold the record for the best sequence of results in the [[Football League]], winning nine matches in succession without conceding a goal.<ref name=\"Secret Stockport\" /> This record ran from January to March 2007, when manager [[Jim Gannon]] led the club to the best form shown by a football club in Football League history.<ref name=\"Our History\" /><ref name=\"Stockport County : Records\" /> This final match in this nine match run was a 3\u20130 home win against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]].<ref name=\"Stockport 3-0 Swindon\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/6408259.stm|title=Stockport 3\u20130 Swindon |accessdate=30 August 2015 |date=3 March 2007  |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nWayne Hennessey, who was on loan to Stockport at the time from Wolves, kept all the clean sheets in his first nine games in professional football.<ref name=\"FL record\" /> He made his footballing debut against [[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]] where Stockport won 2\u20130. During this time, Hennessey received the League Two Player of the Month Award,<ref name=\"Hennessey's heroics secure award\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/6417015.stm |title=Hennessey's heroics secure award |accessdate=15 April 2012 |date=4 March 2007  |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> The other players involved in matches during the record-breaking run are as follows: [[Robert Clare]], [[Michael Rose (footballer, born 1982)|Michael Rose]], [[Ashley Williams (footballer)|Ashley Williams]], [[Gareth Owen (footballer born 1982)|Gareth Owen]], [[Stephen Gleeson]], [[Jason Taylor (English footballer)|Jason Taylor]], [[Adam Griffin]], [[David Poole (footballer)|David Poole]], [[Damien Allen]], [[Anthony Pilkington]], [[Tony Dinning]], [[Dominic Blizzard]], [[Liam Dickinson]], [[Adam Proudlock]], [[Tes Bramble]] and [[Anthony Elding]].<ref name=\"Stockport County datafile\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |title=Stockport County: A Complete Record |first1=Peter |last1=Freeman|first2=Richard |last2=Harnwell |year=1994 |isbn=1-873626-72-X}}\n*{{cite book |title=Football Fans Guide |first1=Janet |last1=Williams|first2=Mark |last2=Johnson |year=1995 |isbn=978-0002187077}}\n*{{cite book |title=On the Edge: The Official Story of Dave Jones  |first1=David |last1=Jones |year=1997 |isbn=978-1871872255}}\n*{{cite book |title=Stockport County Football Club: An A-Z |first1=Dean |last1=Hayes|year=1998 |isbn=9781850586418}}\n*{{cite book |title=Stockport County \u2013 From the Nursery |first=Peter |last=Freeman |year=1999 |isbn=0-9537558-0-0}}\n*{{cite book |title=A Record of British Wartime Football |first=Brian |last=McColl |year=1999 |isbn=978-1-291-84089-6}}\n*{{cite book |title=Stockport County Encyclopaedia and History Update  |first=Peter |last=Freeman |year=2000 |isbn= 978-1874427636}}\n*{{cite book |title=When Friday Night was County Night: Stockport Footballing Memories |first1=Barry |last1=Cheetham|year=2000 |isbn=978-1850587194}}\n*{{cite book |title=Stockport County 100: The Teams First Season in the Football League 1900 - 1901 |first1=Carol Ann |last1=Perry|year=2000 |isbn=978-0905164748}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888\u20132005 |first1=Paul |last1=Smith|first2=Shirley |last2=Smith |year=2005 |isbn=978-0954783044}}\n*{{cite book |title=A Pictorial History of Stockport County 1883 - 2006 |first1=Richard |last1=Harnwell|first2=Phil |last2=Brennan |year=2006 |isbn=978-0955788918}}\n*{{cite book |title=Legends of Stockport County FC |first=Guy |last=Nelson |year=2008 |isbn= 978-1845471958}}\n*{{cite book |title=A Pictorial History of Stockport County 1883- 2011 (The Continuing Story) |first1=Richard |last1=Harnwell|first2=Phil |last2=Brennan |year=2011 |isbn=978-0956984869}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Man from Uruguay: Danny Bergara - A Footballing Journey  |first1=Phil |last1=Brennan |year=2013 |isbn=978-0992785321}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.stockportcounty.com/}}\n*[http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Stockport_County/Stockport_County.htm List of historical Stockport County kits]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070426213631/http://www.manchester2002-uk.com/towns/stockport3.html details of the crest of Stockport]\n\n{{Stockport County F.C.}}\n{{Stockport County F.C. managers}}\n{{Football Conference}}\n{{Former Football League members}}\n{{Football in Greater Manchester}}\n\n[[Category:Stockport County F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in the Metropolitan Borough of Stockport]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1883]]\n[[Category:1883 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:The Combination]]\n[[Category:Lancashire League (football)]]\n[[Category:Former English Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Midland Football League (1889)]]\n[[Category:National League (English football)]]\n[[Category:Companies that have entered administration in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Stockport County\n| image = Stockport County Logo 2014.png\n| alt = Stockport County's crest\n| fullname = Stockport County Football Club\n| nickname = The Hatters; County\n| founded = {{start date and years ago|df=yes|1883}} (as Heaton Norris Rovers)\n| ground = [[Edgeley Park]], [[Stockport]]\n| capacity = 10,852 all seated\n| owner = Mark Stott <ref name=\"Club Statement - Mark Stott\"/>\n| chairman = Richard Park\n| manager = [[Jim Gannon]]\n| league = {{English football updater|StockpoC}}\n| season = {{English football updater|StockpoC2}}\n| position = {{English football updater|StockpoC3}}\n| website = http://www.stockportcounty.com/?site/desktop\n| pattern_la1 = _jomagold19brg\n| pattern_b1  = _jomagold19brg\n| pattern_ra1 = _jomagold19brg\n| pattern_sh1 = _joma19brw\n| pattern_so1 = \n| leftarm1    = FFFFFF\n| body1       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1   = FFFFFF\n| shorts1     = FFFFFF\n| socks1      = 0033FF\n\n|pattern_la2=\n|pattern_b2= _Slavia_17_18_h\n|pattern_ra2=\n|pattern_sh2=_white stripes\n|pattern_so2=\n|leftarm2=FFFFFF\n|body2=FFFFFF\n|rightarm2=FFFFFF\n|shorts2=000080\n|socks2=000080\n\n|pattern_la3=_concordia1920h\n|pattern_b3=_concordia1920h\n|pattern_ra3=_concordia1920h\n|pattern_sh3=\n|pattern_so3=_band_black\n|leftarm3=000000\n|body3=000000\n|rightarm3=000000\n|shorts3=000000\n|socks3=000000\n\n| current = 2019\u201320 National League#National League table\n}}\n'''Stockport County Football Club''' is a professional [[Association football|football]] club in [[Stockport]], England. Formed in 1883 as '''Heaton Norris Rovers''', the team adopted their current name in 1890 after the [[County Borough of Stockport]].<ref name=Complete>{{cite book |last=Freeman |first=Peter |title=Stockport County \u2013 From the Nursery |publisher=  |location= |year=1999 |isbn=0-9537558-0-0}}</ref><ref name=\"Our History\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/the-club/our-history/ | title=Our History| publisher=stockportcounty.com | accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> They have played at [[Edgeley Park]] since 1902,<ref name=\"Stockport County's home since 1902\">{{cite news|url=http://www.stockportcounty.com/club/edgeley-park/|title=Stockport County's home since 1902|publisher=stockportcounty.com|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref> traditionally in blue and white, and are nicknamed The Hatters after the town's former hat-making industry.<ref name=\"Background\">{{cite news | url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Stockport_County/Stockport_County.htm#background| title=Background| work=Historical Kits |accessdate=4 April 2012|last=Moor|first=Dave|date=4 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nStockport County joined [[the Football League]] in 1900 and competed in it continuously from 1905 to 2011. The team spent most of their history in the lower reaches of the Football League, but the 1990s were more successful, with the club competing in the [[EFL Championship|First Division]] for five seasons, and reaching the League Cup semi-finals in 1996\u201397.\n\nAfter a difficult period of financial collapse in the early 2000s which saw the club fall back down the divisions, County started the [[2011\u201312 in English football|2011\u201312]] season in the [[Conference National]], having been relegated from [[Football League Two]] for the first time in their history at the end of [[2010\u201311 in English football|the 2010\u201311 campaign]].<ref name=\"League Two Table 2010-11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/page/DivisionalLeagueTable/0,,10794~201026,00.html |title=League Two Table 2010\u201311 |publisher=The Football League |accessdate=11 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012010808/http://www.football-league.co.uk/page/DivisionalLeagueTable/0%2C%2C10794~201026%2C00.html |archivedate=12 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> At the end of [[2012\u201313 in English football|2012\u201313]], County were relegated again, to the [[Conference North]].<ref name=\"Conference Premier Table 2012-13\">{{cite web | url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/conference-premier/2012-2013| title=Conference Premier Table 2012-13| work=Statto  | accessdate=9 August 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718172113/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/conference-premier/2012-2013 |archivedate=18 July 2014 }}</ref> Having stabilised on and off the pitch, the club won promotion once again at the end of [[2018\u201319 in English football|2018\u201319]], winning the [[National League North]] title.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48080276 National League North: Stockport beat Nuneaton 3\u20130 to secure title and promotion], BBC, 27 April 2019</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Stockport County F.C.}}\n\n===1883\u20131930===\nStockport County was formed in 1883 as Heaton Norris Rovers at McLaughlins Cafe, by a group of pupils, aged 14 -19, from Stockport Sunday School who were also members of the Wycliffe Congregational Church.<ref name=\"Background\" /><ref name=\"The Four Heatons Through Time\">{{cite book |last1=Page |first1=Phil |last2=Littlechilds |first2=Ian |title=The Four Heatons Through Time |publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited  |location= |year=2013 |isbn=9781445620664}}</ref> (Tom Richards ''19'',  Jack Hewitt ''18'', Samuel Riley ''14'', William Riley (Brother of Samuel) ''16'', Tom Machin ''16'', Stan Hockenhull ''17'', Ted Whittle ''15'', William Ridgway ''15'', Ted Simpson ''16'',  Ben Kelly ''15'')<ref name=\"The teenage terrace heroes who set up a football club: Details of Stockport County founders revealed for the first time\">{{cite news | url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/teenage-terrace-heroes-who-set-13947925 | title= The teenage terrace heroes who set up a football club: Details of Stockport County founders revealed for the first time | publisher=Manchester Evening News | date=20 June 2015 |last=Bainbridge|first=Katherine | accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref> and played their first recorded game in October the next year. The club adopted The Hatters as their nickname,<ref name=Complete /> owing to Stockport's history as the centre of the Victorian hat-making industry, a nickname that is shared with [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]].<ref name=\"Background\" /> Heaton Norris Rovers adopted the name Stockport County in 1890<ref name=\"The Four Heatons Through Time\" /> and played in the [[Lancashire League (football)|Lancashire League]] until 1900, when they gained admission to the [[Football League Second Division]].<ref name=\"Lancashire league 1899/00\">{{cite web | url=http://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/NonLeagueTables/LancsL1899-00.htm| title=Lancashire league 1899/00| publisher=footballsite.co.uk | accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> Stockport's first Football League match was against [[Leicester Fosse]] which ended in a 2\u20132 draw.<ref name=\"Our History\" /> In 1901, the first black professional footballer [[Arthur Wharton]], who was 36 at the time, signed for Stockport and made several appearances before retiring from football in 1902.<ref name=\"Arthur Wharton\">{{cite web | url=http://www.100greatblackbritons.com/bios/arthur_wharton-andrew_watson.html| title=Arthur Wharton | work=100 Great Black Britons }}</ref><ref name=\"Arthur Wharton: The first Black Footballer\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/tyne/roots/2003/10/arthur_wharton.shtml | title=Arthur Wharton: The first Black Footballer | work=BBC }}</ref><ref name=\"Secret Stockport\">{{cite book |last1=Page |first1=Phil |last2=Littlechilds |first2=Ian |title=Secret Stockport |publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited  |location= |year=2017 |isbn=9781445651378}}</ref> Stockport left their [[Green Lane (Stockport)|Green Lane]] home in 1902 and moved to [[Edgeley Park]] where they currently reside.<ref name=\"Stockport County's home since 1902\" /><ref name=\"The Four Heatons Through Time\" /><ref name=\"Secret Stockport\" /> At the time Edgeley Park was home to [[Stockport RFC]] until they folded a few years later.<ref name=\"About Stockport County\">{{cite web|title=About Stockport County|url=http://www.stockport.gov.uk/aboutstockport1/stockportcounty/aboutcounty|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100213192316/http://www.stockport.gov.uk/aboutstockport1/stockportcounty/aboutcounty|archivedate=2010-02-13}}</ref>\n\nStockport finished in the bottom three for their first four seasons, and at the end of [[1903\u201304 in English football|1903\u201304]] they failed to gain [[Re-election (Football League)|re-election]].<ref name=\"Division 2 1903/04\">{{cite web | url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1903-04/Div21903-04.htm| title=Division 2 1903/04| publisher=footballsite.co.uk | accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref> They spent one year in the [[Lancashire Combination]] (a league which they won)<ref name=\"England - Lancashire Combination\">{{cite news | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/englancacombhist.html#fin1| title= England \u2013 Lancashire Combination| work=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=11 April 2012|last=Abbink|first=Dinant|date=2 May 2007}}</ref> and the [[Midland League]]. At the end of the season, they were re-admitted to the Football League after being re-elected through the Midland League.<ref name=\"Midland League 1904/05\">{{cite web | url=http://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/NonLeagueTables/ML1904-05.htm| title=Midland League 1904/05| publisher=footballsite.co.uk | accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref> In their first season back in the Football League, Stockport reached the first round of the FA Cup for the first time; however, they were knocked out by [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]].<ref name=\"Stockport County Record while in the Football League\">{{cite web |url=http://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/ClubbyClub/ClubHistories/StockportCounty.htm | title=Stockport County Record while in the Football League| publisher=footballsite.co.uk | accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> Stockport finished the league in 10th position that season.<ref name=\"Division 2 1905/06\">{{cite web | url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1905-06/Div21905-06.htm|title=DIVISION 2 1905/06| publisher=footballsite.co.uk | accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Stockport-County-1914-15-400px.jpg|250px|thumb|left|Photo of the 1913\u201314 Stockport County team]]\n\nStockport remained in the Second Division of the Football League for seven years until [[1912\u201313 in English football|1912\u201313]] when they again had to seek re-election. Stockport gained 22 votes and therefore re-elected.<ref name=\"Division 2 1912/13\">{{cite web | url=http://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1912-13/Div21912-13.htm| title=Division 2 1912/13| publisher=footballsite.co.uk | accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nThomas Evans, Stockport goalkeeper played for the club between 1913\u20131915, after he was scouted in a charity match. His time at Stockport was cut short because of World War One, where he severed in the Army. He survived the war and played three further matches for Stockport before moving back to his native Isle of Man.<ref name=\"Stockport County goalkeeper was a WW1 hero\">{{cite web | url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/in-your-area/stockport-county-goalkeeper-ww1-hero-7672996| title=Stockport County goalkeeper was a WW1 hero| date=26 August 2014| publisher=Manchester Evening News | accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Stockport pay tribute to 13 former players who lost their lives in the great war with a plaque which is displayed outside the ground, which was unveiled by former player and RAF veteran George Haigh.<ref name=\"103-year-old George Haigh helps County pay tribute to the fallen\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/103-year-old-george-haigh-helps-county-pay-tribute-to-the-fallen/| title=103-year-old George Haigh helps County pay tribute to the fallen| date=15 November 2018| publisher=Stockportcounty.com | accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDespite an unsuccessful [[1920\u201321 in English football|1920\u201321]] campaign that saw Stockport end the season bottom of the Second Division, which would normally have seen them face re-election however, they were placed in the new [[Football League Third Division North|Third Division North]].<ref name=\"Division 2 1920/21\">{{cite web | url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1920-21/Div21920-21.htm| title=Division 2 1920/21| publisher=footballsite.co.uk | accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref> After winning five of their first six matches; along with going unbeaten from New Years Day 1921 to Easter Weekend 1922;<ref name=\"Stockport County: A Complete History\">{{cite book |last1=Freeman |first1=Peter |last2=Harnwell |first2=Richard |title=Stockport County: A Complete History |publisher=Breedon Books  |location=Derby |year=1994 |isbn=1-873626-72-X}}</ref> Stockport set the standard for the division and gained their first Football League title when they beat [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] in front of 18,500 fans at Edgeley Park. Albert Williams (the then manager) was presented with the trophy seven days later before the home game with [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]].<ref name=\"Top Hatters' Silver Salvo\">{{cite news | first=Phil | last=Brennan | title=Top Hatters' Silver Salvo | location = Stockport | newspaper=Stockport Express | page = 56 | date=16 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Division 3 (North) 1921/22\">{{cite web| url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1921-22/Div3(N)1921-22.htm| title=Division 3 (North) 1921/22| publisher=footballsite.co.uk| accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> This title win began a remarkable coincidence which has occurred in each of Stockport's first three title winning seasons where Lincoln City have been the last opponents in each of those seasons.<ref name=\"Stockport County: A Complete History\" /> Joe O'Kane; who joined Stockport the previous season, was a major factor in the club's promotion although he left Stockport at the end of the season.<ref name=\"Stockport County: A Complete History\" />\n\nOnce Stockport returned to the Second Division, they struggled and survived an automatic relegation by one point.<ref name=\"DIVISION 2 1922/23\">{{cite web| url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1922-23/Div21922-23.htm| title=DIVISION 2 1922/23| publisher=footballsite.co.uk| accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> The [[1923\u201324 in English football|1923\u201324]] season saw Stockport County finish 13th, one place above Manchester United. This is the only time in history Stockport has achieved a better place finish than Manchester United.<ref name=\"DIVISION 2 1923/24\">{{cite web| url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1923-24/Div21923-24.htm| title=DIVISION 2 1923/24| publisher=footballsite.co.uk| accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> During this campaign Stockport goalkeeper Harry Hardy was called up to play for the England national team and kept a clean sheet in a 4\u20130 win against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]].<ref name=\"County and Country\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/the-club/county-and-country/| title=County and Country| publisher=stockportcounty.com | accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"England Stats - Harry Hardy\">{{cite news | url=http://www.englandstats.com/players.php?pid=439| title=England Stats \u2013 Harry Hardy| work=englandstats.com |accessdate=13 August 2015|last=Naylor|first=Davey|date=4 April 2012}}</ref> He is the only player to be capped at full level by England while on Stockport's books.<ref name=\"England Hero Harry Is One Of A Kind\">{{cite news | first=Phil | last=Brennan | title=England Hero Harry Is One of a Kind | location = Stockport | newspaper=Stockport Express | page = 56 | date=16 May 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hardy England Cap back at Edgeley Park\">{{cite web | url=http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-07-14-hardy-england-cap-911894.aspx| title=Hardy England Cap back at Edgeley Park| publisher=stockportcounty.com | accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Harry Hardy (1895-1969)\">{{cite journal |last1=Jordan |first1=Bernard |last2=Edwards |first2=Leigh |date=14 February 2009|title=Harry Hardy (1895\u20131969) |journal=Stockport County Match Programme Vs. Millwall |pages=28, 29 |location= Stockport}}</ref> It can be noted that Hardy was also selected for England for their 1925 tour of Australia while at Stockport, however as these matches were classified as 'test' matches they are not recognised on international records. <ref name=\"England in Australia in 1925\">{{cite web | url=http://sesasport.com/?p=2069 | title= England in Australia in 1925 | publisher= Sports & Editorial Services Australia | date=24 January 2013 |last=Hay|first=Roy | accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[1925\u201326 in English football|1925\u201326]] saw Stockport returned to the bottom division after finishing bottom of the league and only picking up 25 points.<ref name=\"Division 2 1925/26\">{{cite web| url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1925-26/Div21925-26.htm| title=Division 2 1925/26| publisher=footballsite.co.uk| accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> Stockport finished 6th the next season ([[1926\u201327 in English football|1926\u201327]]) but suffered a 2-point deduction and \u00a3100 fine for fielding an ineligible player after the registration documents for Joe Smith were not received by the Football League.<ref name=\"Did you know? 29 POINTS DEDUCTIONS, DEMOTIONS and EXPULSIONS........\">{{cite web | url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/DYK/DYK29-PointsDeductions.htm| title=Did you know? 29 POINTS DEDUCTIONS, DEMOTIONS and EXPULSIONS........| publisher=footballsite.co.uk | accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nStockport closed out the 1920s in the Third Division North with a 3rd-placed finish in [[1927\u201328 in English football|1927\u201328]].<ref name=\"DIVISION 3 (North) 1927/28\">{{cite web| url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1927-28/Div3(N)1927-28.htm| title=DIVISION 3 (North) 1927/28| publisher=footballsite.co.uk| accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref>   Joe Smith was Stockport's and the division's leading goalscorer in this particular season contributing to 38 of Stockport's 89 goals.<ref name=\"DIVISION 3 (North) 1927/28\" /> Stockport also finished second on two occasions, one in [[1928\u201329 in English football|1928\u201329]];<ref name=\"DIVISION 3 (North) 1928/29\">{{cite web| url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1928-29/Div3(N)1928-29.htm| title=DIVISION 3 (North) 1928/29| publisher=footballsite.co.uk| accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref> Where they amassed 62 points, scored over 100 goals in a season and averaged 10,000 fans for the first time, it was a memorable season, but one that in the end had been disappointing. Stockport won nine of their last 11 matches however it was not been enough to win the league.<ref name=\"Stockport County: A Complete History\" /> Stockport also finished second the following season; [[1929\u201330 in English football|1929\u201330]]<ref name=\"DIVISION 3 (North) 1929/30\">{{cite web| url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1929-30/Div3(N)1929-30.htm| title=DIVISION 3 (North) 1929/30| publisher=footballsite.co.uk| accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref> with an even better record than in the previous season, finishing four points behind the champions [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] despite beating them 2\u20131 away on Christmas Day and 4\u20132 on Boxing Day, 1929.<ref name=\"Stockport County: A Complete History\" /> Frank Newton was Stockport's and the division's leading goalscorer in this particular season contributing to 36 of Stockport's 106 goals,<ref name=\"DIVISION 3 (North) 1929/30\" /> including 5 goals, equalling a club record for goals scored in a match, vs Nelson on 21 September 1929.<ref name=\"The County programme worth \u00a3700\">{{cite web| url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/the-county-programme-worth-700-1025702| title=The County programme worth \u00a3700| date=5 September 2007| publisher=Manchester Evening News| accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1930\u20131950===\nFrom the start of the 1930s, Stockport County played in a home strip of white and black and were nicknamed the 'Lilywhites'.<ref name=\"Our History\" /> The [[1933\u201334 in English football|1933\u201334]] season saw them achieve 115 goals. These included a 13\u20130 home win over [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] on 6 January 1934; Joe Hill made his debut for Stockport scoring twice to making the score 2\u20130 at half time. Hill completed his hat trick on 51 minutes also Percy Downes made a notable performance scoring four of Stockport's goals on this day.<ref name=\"Stockport County: A Complete History\" /><ref name=\"Secret Stockport\" /> This record victory still stands as a Football League record.<ref name=\"Records\">{{cite news |url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/the-club/honours-and-records/|title=Records |publisher=stockportcounty.com|accessdate=29 August 2013|date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Over the course of the 1933\u201334 season Alf Lythgoe scored 46 goals for Stockport.<ref name=\"Netbusters and Record Breakers\">{{cite news | first=Phil | last=Brennan | title=Netbusters and Record Breakers | location = Stockport | newspaper=Stockport Express | page = 59 | date=30 May 2012}}</ref> Another record that still stands in the club's history.<ref name=\"Records\"/> Another first for Stockport was also seen during this season when Stockport's 2\u20131 home defeat to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in the second round of the FA Cup was shown on television.<ref name=\"Netbusters and Record Breakers\" /> Stockport finished third in this season.<ref name=\"Division 3 (North) 1933/34\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1933-34/Div3(N)1933-34.htm|title=Division 3(North) 1933/34|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Main Stand of [[Edgeley Park]], which in 1935 was made of wood, burned down in a fire, destroying all of Stockport County's records before 1935. Besides having to rebuild a significant section of the ground, the club had to piece together historical information.<ref name=\"EDGELEY PARK\">{{cite news|url=https://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=890902|title=EDGELEY PARK|publisher=Historic England |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> The current Main Stand, was built a year later in 1936 and officially opened by [[Charles Sutcliffe]], then President of the Football League.<ref name=\"Stockport County's home since 1902\" /> In [[1936\u201337 in English football|1936\u201337]] County won the Third Division North, gaining 60 points and 23 wins.<ref name=\"DIVISION 3 (North) 1936/37\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1936-37/Div3(N)1936-37.htm|title=DIVISION 3 (North) 1936/37|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref> Towards the end of this season, Stockport had a ten-game unbeaten run that included seven victories before a last-day title decider against [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] in which more than 27,000 fans attended.<ref name=\"Final day drama in 1937\">{{cite news | first=Phil | last=Brennan | title=Final day drama in 1937 | location = Stockport | newspaper=Stockport Express | page = 58 | date=6 June 2012}}</ref> The following season, Stockport finished 22nd out of 22 in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] and were relegated to the Third Division North after only earning 31 points.<ref name=\"DIVISION 2 1937/38\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1937-38/Div21937-38.htm|title=DIVISION 2 1937/38|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[1939\u201340 in English football|1939\u201340]] season football was stopped following Britain's declaration of war and was not resumed until the end of World War II. This was because most British men were sent to the army. Stockport played only two matches in the 1939\u201340 season before war was declared, losing both and being bottom of the league.<ref name=\"DIVISION 3 (North) 1939/40\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1939-40/Div3(N)1939-40.htm|title=DIVISION 3 (North) 1939/40|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref> Regional league competitions were set up; appearances in these tournaments do not count in players' official records. Due to teams having a depleting number of players most teams resigned from football, the clubs that were left to compete used guest players to make up their numbers. The FA Cup was also suspended and replaced with the [[Football League War Cup]].<ref name=\"Keep Calm, Carry on and Play Soccer: The Football League War Cup\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/01/football-league-war-cup.html| title= Keep Calm, Carry on and Play Soccer: The Football League War Cup | publisher=Paste Magazine | date=15 January 2015 | accessdate=28 August 2015|last=Becker|first=Matt|location=Georgia,USA|work=Paste Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIn the first war league after the outbreak of World War II ([[1940\u201341 in English football|1940\u201341]]) Stockport finished in 35th place overall in the [[Football League North and South|Northern Regional League]] after playing 29 games. League standings were calculated by goal average over the course of games played, with some teams playing more than others.<ref name=RSSSF>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng41.html |title=England 1940/41 |first=Peter |last=Kungler |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation (RSSSF) |date=15 February 2003 |accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"A Record of British Wartime Football\">{{cite book |last=McColl |first=Brian |title=A Record of British Wartime Football  |location= |year=2014 | page = 115 |isbn=978-1-291-84089-6}}</ref> In [[1945\u201346 in English football|1945\u201346]], English football still did not have a football season; however, The FA Cup competition was resumed. Stockport was eliminated from the [[1945\u201346 FA Cup]] in the first round after a 3\u20132 aggregate loss to [[Rochdale F.C|Rochdale]].<ref name=\"F.A. Cup 1945/46\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1945-46/F.A.Cup1945-46.html|title=F.A. Cup 1945/46|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref> Also in 1945\u201346 Stockport hosted Doncaster Rovers in a League Three North Cup match, this match would go down in history as the longest ever professional football match, clocking 203 minutes. There was no extra time so matches that were replayed were play to the finish. Stockport went on to lose a second replay 4\u20130.<ref name=\"When extra time had no end: how one match lasted 3hrs and 23mins\">{{cite web | url=http://sesasport.com/?p=2069 | title= When extra time had no end: how one match lasted 3hrs and 23mins | publisher= The Guardian | date=29 March 2018 |last=Burnton|first=Simon | accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref> The first post-war league season [[1946\u201347 in English football|1946\u201347]] saw Stockport finish fourth in the Third Division North with 24 wins and 50 points.<ref name=\"DIVISION 3 (North) 1946/47\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1946-47/Div3(N)1946-47.htm|title=DIVISION 3 (North) 1946/47|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n===1950\u20131999===\n[[File:Stockport County FC League Performance.svg|thumb|300px|right|Chart of yearly table positions of Stockport County in the English football league system]]\nThe 1950s brought little league success, but were notable for goal-scoring by [[Jack Connor (footballer born 1919)|Jack Connor]], whose 140 goals in five seasons are still a club record. These included 13 [[hat-trick]]s (three of which were consecutive \u2013 once against [[Crewe Alexandra F.C|Crewe Alexandra]] and twice against [[Chester City F.C.|Chester]]), two instances of four goals in a match (against [[Workington A.F.C.|Workington]] and [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]]), and two of five goals in a match (against [[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]] and the [[Tranmere Rovers F.C|Tranmere Rovers]]).<ref name=\"Leading scorer Connor an all-time County great\">{{cite news | first=Phil | last=Brennan | title=Leading scorer Connor an all-time County great| location = Stockport | newspaper=Stockport Express | page = 58 | date=13 June 2012}}</ref> When the regional Third Divisions were to be combined into national [[Football League Third Division|Third]] and [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Divisions]] after the [[1957\u201358 in English football|1957\u201358]] campaign, Stockport finished in the top half of the Third Division North and so were placed in the following season's national Third Division.<ref name=\"DIVISION 3 (North) 1957/58\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1957-58/Div3(N)1957-58.htm||title=DIVISION 3 (North) 1957/58|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nStockport spent one season at this level before the club was demoted.<ref name=\"DIVISION 3 1958/59\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1958-59/Div31958-59.htm|title=DIVISION 3 1958/59|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref> Stockport played in the first [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] competition in [[1960\u201361 in English football|1960\u201361]], beating [[Carlisle United F.C|Carlisle United]] in the first round,<ref name=\"Our History\" /> but the club was eliminated in the second round after a 3\u20130 defeat against [[Manchester City F.C|Manchester City]].<ref name=\"LEAGUE CUP 1960/61 Results\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1960-61/LeagueCup1960-61.html|title=LEAGUE CUP 1960/61 Results|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> In the 1964\u201365 FA Cup run Stockport were drawn against reigning Football League champions [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at Anfield. Stockport footed the [[1964\u201365 Football League|Fourth Division]]. Stockport pulled off a shock 1\u20131 draw at Anfield after deservedly taking the lead with enough chances to have won.<ref name=\"Stockport lead - then hold on for shock replay\">{{cite news | url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Images/newspapers/echo/1965-01-30-stockport-267.JPG| title=Stockport lead \u2013 then hold on for shock replay| work=Liverpool Echo |accessdate=12 April 2020|last=Ewards|first=Leslie|date=30 January 1965}}</ref> Unfortunately the replay was a 0\u20132 home defeat after another excellent performance against top class opposition.<ref name=\"FA CUP 1964/65 Results\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1964-65/F.A.Cup1964-65.html|title=LEAGUE CUP 1960/61 Results|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Despite Stockport's ability to match the [[1964\u201365 European Cup]] semi-finalist they finished bottom of the Fourth Division and survived re-election in the [[1964\u201365 in English football|1964\u201365]] season. After finishing bottom of the league with 27 points, the club was re-elected by gaining 45 votes.<ref name=\"DIVISION 4 1964/65\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1964-65/Div41964-65.htm|title=DIVISION 4 1964/65|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref> Also during the 1964\u201365 season, then Stockport Chairman Vic Bernard re-introduced the royal blue strip, colours they still play in.<ref name=\"Our History\" /> Also during this time Bernard hired [[Bert Trautmann]] as the club's general manager. Trautmann's appointment was used to improve the clubs image; Trautmann and Bernard decided to move matches to Friday evenings,<ref name=\"Trautmann The Biography\">{{cite book |last=Rowlands |first=Adam |title=Trautmann The Biography |publisher=DB Publishing  |location= |year=2012 |isbn=978-1780911199}}</ref> this improved revenue, but the team continued to struggle.\nDue to Trautmann's connections to his native Germany, a friendly was arranged at the end of 1964-65 season with [[Hamburger SV]] which Stockport lost 3-1. During the following pre-season Stockport toured Germany where they played 3 friendlies in 5 days; [[VfL Bochum]], [[SC Opel R\u00fcsselsheim]] and a return match against Hamburger SV. Trautmann resigned from his position in 1966<ref name=\"Trautmann The Biography\" />Two seasons later Stockport returned to Third Division by winning the Fourth Division in [[1966\u201367 in English football|1966\u201367]] after gaining 64 points.<ref name=\"DIVISION 4 1966/67\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1966-67/Div41966-67.htm|title=DIVISION 4 1966/67|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter the club was relegated in [[1969\u201370 in English football|1969\u201370]], the 1970s, and 1980s consisted of little other than mediocrity and struggling against relegation. George Best made three appearances for Stockport in 1975, scoring two goals.<ref name=\"Secret Stockport\" /><ref name=\"Football mourns George Best\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4466944.stm|title=Football mourns George Best|publisher= BBC Sport|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> In February 1984 Stockport competed in their first [[Football League Trophy|Associate Members' Cup]] match against [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] in a competition their chairman at the time' Dragan Lukic' helped create. The matched finished 2\u20132 after extra time and as so was decided in a penalty shoot-out; the first in Stockport's history. Stockport went on to lose 3\u20130 on penalties.<ref name=\"County's First Football League Trophy Team\">{{cite journal |last=Watts |first=Ian |date=18 August 2015 |title=County's First Football League Trophy Team |journal=Stockport County Match Programme Vs. North Ferriby United |page=14 |location= Stockport |publisher= Amberley Court Associates LtD}}</ref> The introduction of automatic promotion and relegation between the Football League and the [[Football Conference|Conference]] was not a good sign for Stockport, and in [[1986\u201387 in English football|1986\u201387]] they had just six points from 13 games and faced a real prospect of [[non-League football]], exemplified by being eliminated from the [[FA Cup]] by [[Caernarfon Town F.C.|Caernarfon Town]].<ref name=\"FA CUP 1986/87\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1986-87/F.A.Cup1986-87.html|title=FA CUP 1986/87|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>  [[Colin Murphy (footballer, born 1950)|Colin Murphy]] was brought in for his second spell as manager. Stockport gained 45 points from their final 31 games and survived, although Murphy left shortly after the end of the season.<ref name=Complete />\n\n[[Danny Bergara]] was appointed as manager in March 1989, quickly transforming the team, and automatic promotion was gained in [[1990\u201391 in English football|1990\u201391]].<ref name=\"DIVISION 4 1990/91\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1990-91/Div41990-91.htm|title=DIVISION 4 1990/91|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> The next three seasons saw Stockport make the play-offs, losing 2\u20131 to Burnley in 1994. Stockport finishing with 9 men after Michael Wallace was sent off for spitting at Ted McMinn and Chris Beaumont was dismissed. There was trouble in the stands due to the manner of the defeat.<ref name=\"Football Play-Offs: County fall short as Burnley go up: Parkinson makes the difference\">{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-play-offs-county-fall-short-as-burnley-go-up-parkinson-makes-the-difference-1439518.html| title=Football Play-Offs: County fall short as Burnley go up: Parkinson makes the difference|work=The Independent|last1=Metcalf|first1=Rupert| date=30 May 1994|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1995 Bergara was sacked after an altercation with then-chairman Brendan Elwood,<ref name=\"Stockport sack Bergara\">{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/stockport-sack-bergara-1613775.html| title=Stockport sack Bergara  | work=The Independent  | date=April 1995 | accessdate=15 April 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705215049/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/stockport-sack-bergara-1613775.html |archivedate=5 July 2015 }}</ref> and [[Dave Jones (football manager)|Dave Jones]] was appointed manager in April of that year.<ref name=\"Dave Jones Factfile\">{{cite news |title=Dave Jones factfile|work=Telegraph| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2995736/Dave-Jones-factfile.html | location=London | date=3 January 2001 | accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> A new all-seater, Cheadle End, holding just over 5,000 in capacity, was opened at the start of the [[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396]] season.<ref name=\"Stockport County's home since 1902\" /> Although this particular season was unremarkable, the club reached the third round of the [[FA Cup]], where they faced holders [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]. Stockport reached a 2\u20132 draw with Everton at [[Goodison Park]],<ref name=\"Everton v Stockport County, 07 January 1996\">{{cite news|url=http://www.11v11.com/matches/everton-v-stockport-county-07-january-1996-217152/|title=Everton v Stockport County, 07 January 1996|publisher=11v11.com|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> and for the replay ten days later over 11,000 gathered at [[Edgeley Park]] to witness Everton's late winner in a 3\u20132 victory.<ref name=\"Stockport County v Everton, 17 January 1996\">{{cite news|url=http://www.11v11.com/matches/stockport-county-v-everton-17-january-1996-217162/|title=Stockport County v Everton, 17 January 1996|publisher=11v11.com|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1996\u201397 in English football#Stockport County's Magical Season|1996\u201397]] campaign proved to be the most successful in the club's history. They finished second in the Second Division<ref name=\"DIVISION 1 1996/97\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1996-97/Div21996-97.htm|title=DIVISION 1 1996/97|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> and reached the semi-final of the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]], knocking out three [[Premier League|Premiership]] teams ([[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]) on the way before losing to [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] 2\u20131 on aggregate.<ref name=\"Coca-Cola Cup 1996/97\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1996-97/LeagueCup1996-97.html|title=Coca-Cola Cup 1996/97|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Before the start of the 1997\u201398 season, Dave Jones left for Southampton. [[Gary Megson]] left [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] to take over as manager and in his first season Stockport finished eighth, just two places off the playoffs to reach the Premiership \u2013 the club's best ever league placing.<ref name=\"DIVISION 1 1997/98\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1997-98/Div11997-98.htm|title=DIVISION 1 1997/98|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the following [[1998-99 in English football|1998\u201399]] season saw Stockport finish 16th, winning just 3 of their final 14 matches. A 5\u20130 defeat at relegated [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] on the final day signalled the end of Megson's time at Edgeley Park.<ref>{{cite news |title=Megson sacked by Stockport|work=The Independent, 26 June 1999| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-megson-sacked-by-stockport-1102551.html | location=London | first=Paul | last=Walker | date=26 June 1999 | accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> The club decided to promote from within and [[Andy Kilner]] was soon put in charge. He had an encouraging start to his management at County having defeated Manchester City, 2\u20131 at Maine Road;<ref name=\"Championship 1999/2000 Match 18\">{{cite news|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/schedule/eng-championship-1999-2000-spieltag/18/|title=Championship 1999/2000 \" 18. Round|publisher=worldfootball.net|accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref>\nAnd by Boxing Day the club were sixth, holding a playoff spot.<ref name=\"Championship 1999/2000 Match 24\">{{cite news|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/schedule/eng-championship-1999-2000-spieltag/24/|title=Championship 1999/2000 \" 24. Round|publisher=worldfootball.net|accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2000\u20132010===\nAfter their win over Manchester City, the team then went a club-record 19 games without a victory, eventually finishing the [[1999-00 in English football|1999\u20132000]] season 17th,<ref name=\"DIVISION 1 1999/2000\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/1999-00/Div11999-00.htm|title=DIVISION 1 1999/2000|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> with two late wins helping stave off relegation. The [[2000-01 in English football|2000\u201301]] season saw them again narrowly avoid relegation, finishing 19th overall.<ref name=\"DIVISION 1 2000/01\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/2000-01/Div12000-01.htm|title=DIVISION 1 2000/01|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> The [[2001-02 in English football|2001\u201302]] season turned out to be the club's worst ever season at the time. With Stockport already bottom of the league, a 4\u20130 home defeat to [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] saw manager Kilner sacked.<ref name=\"Struggling Stockport fire Kilner by unilateral consent\">{{cite news  | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/oct/30/newsstory.sport1 | title=Struggling Stockport fire Kilner by unilateral consent | work=The Guardian |accessdate=30 August 2015 |last=Wilson|first=Andy| date=30 October 2001}}</ref> Former England international [[Carlton Palmer]] was appointed in November 2001.<ref name=\"Stockport appoint Palmer\">{{cite news |title=Stockport appoint Palmer|work=Telegraph| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/championship/3016305/Stockport-appoint-Palmer.html | location=London | date=6 November 2001 | accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Palmer named as Stockport boss\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/nov/06/newsstory.sport10\n|title=Palmer named as Stockport boss|work=The Guardian| date=6 November 2001 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Stockport gamble on outspoken Palmer\">{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/championship/3016276/Stockport-gamble-on-outspoken-Palmer.html| title=Stockport gamble on outspoken Palmer| work=Telegraph |accessdate=9 August 2015|last=Johnson|first=William|date=6 November 2001}}</ref> Palmer subsequently failed to stop Stockport being relegated in [[2001\u201302 in English football|2001\u201302]]<ref name=\"DIVISION 1 2001/02\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/2001-02/Div12001-02.htm|title=DIVISION 1 2001/02|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref> or to build a team capable of challenging for a return the next season.<ref name=\"DIVISION 2 2002/03\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/2002-03/Div22002-03.htm|title=DIVISION 2 2002/03|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe summer of 2003 saw the club change ownership, as Elwood sold the club to [[Sale Sharks]] owner Brian Kennedy in a move that would see Sale play their home games at Edgeley Park. A new company was created, called 'Cheshire Sport',<ref name=\"Sharks to merge with Stockport\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/2996279.stm|title=Sharks to merge with Stockport|date=2 May 2003|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> which would have ownership of Stockport County, Sale Sharks and the Edgeley Park stadium. The [[2003-04 in English football|2003\u201304]] season saw Palmer sacked after another poor start to the season, following home defeats to [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool]] and Blackpool in the space of a week. [[John Hollins]], who had been Director of Football during Palmer's reign, took over as caretaker manager,<ref name=\"Stockport sack Palmer\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/3122286.stm|title=Stockport sack Palmer|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Palmer's farewell shot\">{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/palmers-farewell-shot-1152341|title=Palmer's farewell shot|publisher=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref> but was replaced full-time by former [[Northern Ireland]] manager [[Sammy McIlroy]].\n<ref name=\"McIlroy quits NI for Stockport\">{{cite news|title=McIlroy quits NI for Stockport|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/3195082.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=15 October 2003|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> Following more relegation worries, an 11-match unbeaten run saw the club again climb to safety at the end of the season. [[Sammy McIlroy]] continued as manager in the [[2004-05 in English football|2004\u201305]] season; poor results led to his sacking and the appointment of [[Chris Turner (footballer born 1958)|Chris Turner]] one year later.<ref name=\"Turner named as Stockport manager\">{{cite news|title=Turner named as Stockport manager|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/4106123.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=17 December 2004|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nHowever, another relegation followed<ref name=\"LEAGUE 1 2004/05\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/2004-05/League12004-05.htm|title=LEAGUE 1 2004/05|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"STOCKPORT COUNTY 2004/05 results\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/2004-05/ClubResults/2004-05.StockportCounty.html|title=STOCKPORT COUNTY 2004/05 results|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>, and Turner resigned after one year in charge after a 6\u20130 defeat to local rivals [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] that left County five points adrift of safety and facing a third relegation in four years.<ref name=\"Manager Turner leaves Stockport\">{{cite news|title=Manager Turner leaves Stockport|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/4562506.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=27 December 2005|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> [[2005-06 in English football|2005\u201306]] saw Stockport County change owners again. After reportedly losing \u00a34m,<ref name=\"No more cash for Sharks and County\">{{cite web|title=No more cash for Sharks and County|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/manchester/content/articles/2005/11/22/221105_sale_stockport_feature.shtml|work=BBC News|date=22 November 2005|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> Cheshire Sports chairman Brian Kennedy handed ownership of the club to the Supporters Trust, whose aim was to rescue the club from revenue loss, eventually break even and turn Stockport County into a community based football club. \n\nFormer player [[Jim Gannon]] was placed in charge, initially as caretaker-manager.<ref name=\"Gannon unveiled as Stockport boss\">{{cite news|title=Gannon unveiled as Stockport boss|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/4620446.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=17 January 2006|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> He led the club to safety in [[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306]],<ref name=\"LEAGUE 2 2005/06\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/2005-06/League22005-06.htm|title=LEAGUE 2 2005/06|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> and County sustained a promotion challenge the next season, eventually missing out on the [[Football League Two|League Two]] playoffs on goal difference.<ref name=\"LEAGUE 2 2006/07\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/2006-07/League22006-07.htm|title=LEAGUE 2 2006/07|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> The club also set a new Football League record on 3 March 2007 when they beat Swindon Town 3\u20130, recording nine consecutive wins without conceding a goal.<ref name=\"Our History\" /><ref name=\"Stockport County : Records\">{{cite web | url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/stockport-county/records| title=Stockport County : Records| work=Statto  | accessdate=9 August 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703003713/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/stockport-county/records |archivedate=3 July 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"LEAGUE 2 2006/07\" />\n\nAt the start of the 2007\u201308 season it was learned that former manager Danny Bergara had died.<ref name=\"Stockport hero Danny Bergara dies\">{{cite web|title=Stockport hero Danny Bergara dies|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/6917615.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=26 July 2007|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> Stockport County continued their success, despite losing an [[FA Cup]] first round replay away to [[Non-League football|non-League]] [[Staines Town F.C.|Staines Town]] on penalties.<ref name=\"F.A. Cup 2007/08 Results\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/2007-08/F.A.Cup2007-08.html|title=F.A. Cup 2007/08 Results|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> The early months of 2008 saw Stockport equal a league record of eight consecutive away victories.<ref name=\"Stockport boss has young vision\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/7305219.stm| title=Stockport boss has young vision| work=BBC News |accessdate=9 August 2015|last=Oliver|first=Pete|date=19 March 2008}}</ref> Approaching the end of the season, they had an outside chance to qualify for promotion automatically but missed out, finishing the season in fourth place.<ref name=\"LEAGUE 2 2007/08\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/2007-08/League22007-08.htm|title=LEAGUE 2 2007/08|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> However, after beating [[Wycombe Wanderers]] 2\u20131 on aggregate in the play-off semi-final,<ref>{{cite web |title=County win 2\u20131 on aggregate|work=Manchester Evening News |date=17 May 2008| url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/stockport_county/s/1050131_stockport_1_wycombe_0_county_win_21_on_agg}}</ref> Stockport played [[Rochdale A.F.C|Rochdale]] at [[Wembley]] in the [[2008 Football League Two play-off Final|final]], coming from behind to secure a 3\u20132 victory and earn promotion to [[Football League One|League One]] for the next season.<ref name=\"Stockport 3\u20132 Rochdale\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7416601.stm|title=Stockport 3\u20132 Rochdale|date=26 May 2008|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=20 June 2009|last=Fletcher|first=Paul}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dickinson strike sends Stockport into raptures|work=The Independent, 27 May 2008| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/rochdale-2-stockport-county-3-dickinson-strike-sends-stockport-into-raptures-834625.html | location=London | first=Conrad | last=Leach | date=27 May 2008 | accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"STOCKPORT COUNTY 2007/08 results\">{{cite news|url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/2007-08/ClubResults/2007-08.StockportCounty.html|title=STOCKPORT COUNTY 2007/08 results|publisher=footballsite.co.uk|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:County Legends.JPG|300px|thumb|Stockport County players [[Anthony Pilkington]], [[Carl Baker]], [[Stephen Gleeson]] and [[Tommy Rowe]] in December 2008]]\n\nDuring the 2008\u201309 season, Stockport defied the odds by challenging for a play-off place, but their form dipped during the final months of the season, which saw them slip to mid-table. Gannon was approached by [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C|Brighton & Hove Albion]] and the approach was accepted by Stockport, but after talks with the chairman of Brighton, Gannon rejected the job and stayed at Stockport.<ref name=\"Gannon rejects Brighton approach\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/7908756.stm|title=Gannon rejects Brighton approach|date=26 February 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=20 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 2009, Stockport County was placed into administration following a battle to repay creditors.<ref name=\"Stockport go into administration\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/8027353.stm|title=Stockport go into administration|date=30 April 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=20 June 2009}}</ref> This followed a petition by a creditor to repay a loan of around \u00a3300,000. The club had also struggled to repay a tax debt of \u00a3250,000 to [[Her Majesty's Revenue and Customs]]<ref name=\"Stockport enter administration after failing to pay creditors\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/apr/30/stockport-county-administration-football|title=Stockport enter administration after failing to pay creditors|date=30 April 2009|work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref>. On 16 December 2009 the team's training ground was put up for sale.<ref name=\"County's Manor up for sale\">{{cite news|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/sport/football/stockport_county/s/1186282_countys_manor_up_for_sale|title=County's Manor up for sale|work=Manchester Evening News|date=16 December 2009|accessdate=20 February 2012|last=Dawson|first=Rob}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 June 2009, [[Leonard Curtis]], administrator of Stockport County Football Club, announced that they had agreed to terms with the Melrose Consortium for the sale of the club.<ref name=\"Deal agreed for Stockport buy-out\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/8098042.stm|title=Deal agreed for Stockport buy-out|date=12 June 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=20 June 2009}}</ref> Paul Reeves, one of the joint administrators, commented that, \"Whilst a deal has been agreed, it is subject to the Melrose Consortium obtaining landlord approval. This is a positive step to safeguarding the club's future.\" The Melrose Consortium, consisting of \"a group of businessmen with a sporting background\" headed by ex [[Manchester City]] player [[Jim Melrose]] said, \"We look forward to developing a fruitful relationship with [[Sale Sharks]] and [[Stockport Metropolitan Borough Council]] which will provide the basis for a successful future for Stockport County Football Club.\"<ref name=\"Stockport set to be rescued by sale to Melrose consortium\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/blogs/football-spy/league-one/Stockport-set-to-be-rescued-by-sale-to-Melrose-consortium-article86757.html |title=Stockport set to be rescued by sale to Melrose consortium|last=Gripper|first=Ann|date=12 June 2009|work=Mirror|accessdate=8 September 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607050529/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/blogs/football-spy/league-one/Stockport-set-to-be-rescued-by-sale-to-Melrose-consortium-article86757.html|archivedate=7 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe immediate aims of the Melrose Consortium were described as being to \"...guarantee football at Edgeley Park next season and to secure the services of redundant manager, and Stockport legend, Jim Gannon\". On 3 July 2009 Administrators agreed to a [[Trading while insolvent (UK)|Company Voluntary Arrangement (CVA)]] with previous shareholders and creditors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305224109/http://www.stockportcounty.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10419~1712966,00.html|title=Official Statement|publisher=stockportcounty.com|date=3 July 2009| accessdate= 19 September 2009|archiveurl=http://www.stockportcounty.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10419~1712966,00.html|archivedate=7 June 2012}}</ref> Gannon took over as manager at [[Scottish Premier League]] side [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]], causing Stockport fans to worry that he would be poaching young players in the forthcoming weeks. [[Gary Ablett (English footballer)|Gary Ablett]], former manager of [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] reserves, was appointed manager on 8 July 2009 following talks with the (prospective) new owners,<ref name=\"Ablett named County boss\">{{cite news|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/sport/football/stockport_county/s/1124910_ablett_named_county_boss|title=Ablett named County boss|work=Manchester Evening News|date=8 July 2009|last=Dawson|first=Rob|accessdate=22 February 2012}}</ref> although the Melrose Consortium had still not taken over, and in fact never did take over the club. In March 2010 it was announced that a new consortium, the '2015 Group', had been given exclusivity to work towards a takeover of the club.<ref name=\"Second group in bid for Stockport\">{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/second-group-in-bid-for-stockport-886524|title=Second group in bid for Stockport|work=Manchester Evening News|date=12 January 2013|accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2010s: Dark Days===\nThe purchase of Stockport County by the self-styled '2015 Group' of investors was approved by [[the Football League]] at its May 2010 meeting, with the takeover announced on 17 June 2010.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dawson |first1=Rob |title=Stockport takeover boost |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/stockport-takeover-boost-889686 |website=Manchester Evening News |date=15 May 2010}}</ref> Following the takeover, the club announced that previous manager [[Gary Ablett (English footballer)|Gary Ablett]] had been dismissed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Simpson named as Stockport boss |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/other-sport/amateur-sport/simpson-named-as-stockport-boss-3401351 |website=Liverpool Echo |date=13 July 2010}}</ref> This came after one of the poorest seasons in the football club's history, finishing bottom of [[League One]], with just five wins and 25 points for the entire campaign.<ref name=\"League One 2009/10\">{{cite news |url= https://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/Seasons/2009-10/League12009-10.htm |title= League One 2009/10 |publisher= footballsite.co.uk |date= 29 May 2010 |accessdate= 8 September 2013}}</ref>  Despite the new ownership pledging to \"rebuild the club from top to bottom\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Nightmare ends with the dawn of new era |last=Dawson|first=Rob|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/stockportexpress/sport/football/stockport_county/s/1263090_nightmare_ends_with_the_dawn_of_new_era |work=Stockport Express |date=23 June 2010 |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref> but the club's new era got off to a poor start. It was widely reported that former manager [[Jim Gannon]] would return, after being made redundant in April 2009 by the club's administrators. However, no agreement was reached with Gannon, and in the summer of 2010, Stockport appointed former [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] boss [[Paul Simpson (footballer)|Paul Simpson]] as manager.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/8754631.stm | title=Paul Simpson named Stockport County Manager | publisher=BBC Sport | date=12 July 2010 | accessdate=5 April 2011}}</ref> However, Gannon's former assistant, [[Peter Ward (footballer born 1964)|Peter Ward]] \u2013 who, like Gannon also played for the club in the 1990s \u2013 did return as assistant manager.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stockport dismiss manager Simpson |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/9338129.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=4 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Fleetwood 2.jpg|225px|thumb|Stockport County players celebrate a goal in 2011]]\n\nSimpson's reign came at a tumultuous for County, as the club struggled with the hangover from more than 12 months in administration and relegation back to [[League Two]]. With Stockport close to the relegation zone, Simpson was sacked after only six months in charge.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stockport sack Simpson |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/stockport-sack-simpson-850892 |website=Manchester Evening News |date=5 January 2011}}</ref> However, with no proper succession plan in place, [[Peter Ward (footballer born 1964)|Peter Ward]] was appointed as interim manager, with former [[Wigan Athletic]] boss [[Ray Mathias]] brought in as assistant.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ray Mathias |url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/managers/ray-mathias/ |website=League Managers Association}}</ref> This arrangement lasted for only two months, as the chaotic period at the club continued; in March 2011, after only 12 games and with the club in very real danger of relegation, Mathias was asked to replace Ward as interim manager, with the latter returning to the assistant manager role.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dawson |first1=Rob |title=Ray Mathias takes over in Hatters' job switch |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/ray-mathias-takes-over-in-hatters-855937 |website=Manchester Evening News |date=10 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nDespite an upturn in performances and results under Mathias, County fell short of their survival target; the club were relegated into the [[National League (English football)|Conference National]] for the first time in their history, after 106 years in the [[Football League]].<ref name=\"Crewe 2-0 Stockport\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/13174427|title=Crewe 2\u20130 Stockport |accessdate=30 August 2015 |date=30 April 2011  |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nAfter relegation into the Conference National, the club's extraordinary period of upheaval continued. In the summer of 2011, Mathias was appointed as permanent manager.<ref name=\"Mathias chosen for Hatters job\">{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11762/6951632/mathias-chosen-for-hatters-job  |title=Mathias chosen for Hatters job\n|publisher=Sky Sports |date=25 May 2011 |accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> However, before the pre-season campaign got underway, he was dismissed when a Liverpool-based businessman tried \u2013 and ultimately failed<ref name=\"Tony Evans resigns directorship of Stockport County\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14929259  |title=Tony Evans resigns directorship of Stockport County  |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 July 2011 |accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> \u2013 to buy the club, replacing Mathias with former [[Germany national football team|German international]] [[Dietmar Hamann]].<ref name=\"Dietmar Hamann takes over as Stockport County boss\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14033079  |title=Dietmar Hamann takes over as Stockport County boss |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 July 2011 |accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nHamann, who had no prior managerial experience, did poorly at Stockport, and won only three of 19 matches before resigning in November 2011.<ref name=\"Dietmar Hamann resigns as Stockport County manager\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15620388.stm |title = Dietmar Hamann resigns as Stockport County manager|accessdate=7 November 2011|date=7 November 2011|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|text=''\"To see County get relegated with such a low level of points and then see it happen the following year was incredibly disappointing considering the amount of work we had put in...For three-and-half years worth of  work to be undone in two years was devastating and to see it continue this year was really difficult..\"''|sign=Jim Gannon's comments on Stockport's two successive relegations<ref name=\"Jim Gannon: It's devastating to see my hard work at Stockport undone\">{{cite news | url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/jim-gannon-its-devastating-to-see-876685| title=Jim Gannon: It's devastating to see my hard work at Stockport undone| work=Manchester Evening News |accessdate=12 April 2020|last=Dawsom|first=Rob|date=24 November 2011}}</ref>}}\n\nWith the club now looking in serious danger of a third successive relegation, Stockport turned to Jim Gannon to return for a second stint as manager and Director of Football.<ref name=\"Jim Gannon appointed Stockport County director of football\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/15732895  |title=Jim Gannon appointed Stockport County director of football |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 November 2011 |accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> In Gannon's first match back at the club, the team put in a spirited performance, but lost a match 2\u20131 to joint-leaders [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]], who achieved a record attendance in the fixture at their Highbury ground.<ref name=\"Fleetwood 2-1 Stockport\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/15704910.stm | title=Fleetwood 2\u20131 Stockport| date=19 November 2011| publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> After overseeing an improvement in performances, Gannon managed Stockport to their first back-to-back wins in over three years \u2013 last achieved in his first stint as manager \u2013 with 1\u20130 victories over [[Wrexham F.C|Wrexham]]<ref name=\"Stockport 1-0 Wrexham\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17083269| title=Stockport 1\u20130 Wrexham| publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> and [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]].<ref name=\"Darlington 0-1 Stockport\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17162949| title=Darlington 0\u20131 Stockport| publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> Over the remainder of the 2011/12 campaign, Gannon steered Stockport away from the Conference National relegation zone, winning eight of the last 15 league games to finish 16th in the final table.<ref name=\"Stockport County 2011-2012 : English Conference Premier Table\">{{cite web | url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/stockport-county/2011-2012/table| title=Stockport County 2011\u20132012 : English Conference Premier Table| work=Statto  | accessdate=9 August 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703014808/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/stockport-county/2011-2012/table |archivedate=3 July 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Stockport County Players 2012.jpg|thumb|left|The Stockport County squad, April 2012]]\n\nWith his playing budget severely restricted,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dawson |first1=Rob |title=Cruel County cuts kind in long run \u2013 Jim Gannon |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/cruel-county-cuts-kind-in-long-680905 |website=Manchester Evening News |date=2 February 2012}}</ref> Gannon once again focused on the youth development which had served him so well in previous campaigns ahead of the [[2012\u201313 in English football|2012/13 season]]; young players such as [[Danny Whitehead]], Danny Hattersley and Ian Ormson regularly featured in match day squads. The club regained sole tenancy of their Edgeley Park stadium for the first time in nine years from the beginning of the season, after [[Sale Sharks]] relocated to [[Salford Red Devils|Salford City Reds']] home ground.<ref name=\"It's business as usual for County as Sale move out\">{{cite news | url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/sport/football/stockport_county/s/1490299_its-business-as-usual-for-county-as-sale-move-out?all_comments=1| title=It's business as usual for County as Sale move out| work=Manchester Evening News |accessdate=4 April 2012|last=Collins|first=Ben|date=4 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sale Sharks confirm groundshare with Salford City Reds\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/17461665| title=Sale Sharks confirm groundshare with Salford City Reds| work=BBC Sport |accessdate=29 August 2015|date=4 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nHowever, turmoil soon returned to the club. On 15 January 2013 former ''fcbusiness'' magazine editor Ryan McKnight was named as the new Chief Executive Officer at the club, becoming the youngest CEO in UK football.<ref name=\"Stockport County: Ryan McKnight named chief executive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21025602 |title=Stockport County: Ryan McKnight named chief executive  | publisher= BBC Sport |date=15 January 2013|accessdate= 8 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Stockport County Appoint Former fcbusiness Editor as CEO\">{{cite web | url=https://fcbusiness.co.uk/news/article/newsitem=2207/title=stockport+county+appoint+former+fcbusiness+editor+as+ceo| title=Stockport County Appoint Former fcbusiness Editor as CEO| work=fcbusiness  | accessdate=15 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310122158/https://fcbusiness.co.uk/news/article/newsitem=2207/title=stockport+county+appoint+former+fcbusiness+editor+as+ceo |archivedate=10 March 2016 }}</ref> Gannon was subsequently sacked for a second time,<ref name=\"Stockport County: Jim Gannon sacked after 14 months in charge\">{{cite news|title=Stockport County: Jim Gannon sacked after 14 months in charge |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21037493  | publisher= BBC Sport |accessdate=8 September 2013 |date=16 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Stockport County Relieve Gannon of Duties\">{{cite web | url=http://www.league-clubs.co.uk/stockport-county-relieve-gannon-of-duties/| title=Stockport County Relieve Gannon of Duties| work=Leagueclubs.co.uk  | accessdate=16 January 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704170235/http://www.league-clubs.co.uk/stockport-county-relieve-gannon-of-duties/ |archivedate=7 April 2020 }}</ref> following the 3\u20131 home defeat by [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] on 16 January 2013. He was replaced by Bosnian-Swiss [[Darije Kalezi\u0107]], who had never managed in English football previously.<ref name=\"New manager announced\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006065849/http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-01-24-new-manager-616657.aspx| title=New manager announced| work=stockportcounty.com  | accessdate=12 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-01-24-new-manager-616657.aspx |archivedate=24 January 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Darije Kalezic: Stockport County appoint Jim Gannon's successor\">{{cite news|title=Darije Kalezic: Stockport County appoint Jim Gannon's successor|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21185836 | publisher= BBC Sport |accessdate= 12 April 2020 |date=28 January 2013}}</ref> The Kalezi\u0107 era was as swift as it was disastrous; he was dismissed after only two months after a rapid deterioration in results, which left the club in serious danger of relegation to the [[National League North|Conference North]].<ref name=\"Kalezic leaves Edgeley Park\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924110620/http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-03-20-kalezic-leaves-edgeley-park-725820.aspx| title=Kalezic leaves Edgeley Park| work=stockportcounty.com  | accessdate=12 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-03-20-kalezic-leaves-edgeley-park-725820.aspx |archivedate=20 March 2013 }}</ref> He was then succeeded by [[Ian Bogie]],<ref name=\"Ian Bogie named new County manager\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924110618/http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-03-20-bogie-takes-over-725828.aspx| title=Ian Bogie named new County manager| work=stockportcounty.com  | accessdate=12 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-03-20-bogie-takes-over-725828.aspx |archivedate=20 March 2013 }}</ref> but he was unable to turn the club's form around, and they were relegated on the final day after a defeat to title challengers [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]] \u2013 the club's third relegation in four seasons, which left them playing in the sixth tier for the first time in their history.<ref name=\"Kidderminster 4 \u2013 0 Stockport\">{{cite news|title= Kidderminster 4 \u2013 0 Stockport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22133379 | publisher= BBC Sport |accessdate= 8 September 2013 |date=20 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the difficulties did not stop there for County. The club announced that it was to lose its full-time status, proceeding with a part-time model<ref name=\"Stockport County go part time\">{{cite web | url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/stockport-county-go-part-time-3158168| title= Stockport County go part time| publisher= Manchester Evening News |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 26 April 2013 }}</ref>. The start to life in the Conference North was poor, with Stockport picking up only one draw and four defeats from their first five league matches; Bogie resigned in late August 2013, with the club second from bottom of the league.<ref name=\"Stockport County: Ian Bogie resignation 'shocked' board\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/23944162| title= Stockport County: Ian Bogie resignation 'shocked' board| publisher= BBC Sport |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 3 September 2013 }}</ref> Alan Lord, former assistant to both Jim Gannon and Peter Ward, was appointed manager in his place, becoming County's ninth boss in a little over three years.<ref name=\"Board Statement regarding Ian Bogie's resignation\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103202657/http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-08-31-bogie-statement-1027819.aspx| title=Board Statement regarding Ian Bogie's resignation| work=stockportcounty.com  | accessdate=12 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-08-31-bogie-statement-1027819.aspx |archivedate=31 August 2013}}</ref> CEO McKnight announced his resignation in April 2014, stating he would leave in early May 2014.<ref name=\"Club Statement: Ryan McKnight\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924110741/http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2014-04-08-club-statement-ryan-mcknight-1476144.aspx| title=Club Statement: Ryan McKnight| work=stockportcounty.com  | accessdate=12 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2014-04-08-club-statement-ryan-mcknight-1476144.aspx|archivedate=8 April 2014 }}</ref> Lord managed to steady the ship for County, finishing mid-table in the 2013[[2014-15 in English football|\u2013]]14 season<ref name=\"Skrill North Table 2013/14\">{{cite web | url=https://www.thenationalleague.org.uk/archive2027-match-info/tables?table_id=d-7571 | title= Skrill North Table 2013/14| publisher= National League |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 26 April 2014 }}</ref>.The following campaign, Lord then also steered the Hatters to a slightly improved mid-table position<ref name=\"National League North Table 2013/14\">{{cite web | url=https://www.thenationalleague.org.uk/archive2701-match-info/tables?table_id=d-10244| title= National League North Table 2013/14 |publisher= National League |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 25 April 2015}}</ref>, but stepped down before the end of the [[2014-15 in English football|2014\u201315]] season to become Director of Football.<ref name=\"Club Statement: Regarding Alan Lord's Position\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230549/http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/board-statement-2398923.aspx| title=Club Statement: Regarding Alan Lord's Position| work=stockportcounty.com  | accessdate=12 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/board-statement-2398923.aspx|archivedate=13 April 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"Stockport County boss Alan Lord steps down at Edgeley Park\">{{cite news|last1=Partington |first1=Richard |title=Stockport County boss Alan Lord steps down at Edgeley Park |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/stockport-county-boss-alan-lord-9038627 | publisher= Manchester Evening News |accessdate= 9 August 2015 |date= 14 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, The Stockport County board of directors issued an open statement about the future aspirations of the football club, named the 'Moving Forward' Document.<ref name=\"Stockport County possess 2020 vision\">{{cite news | url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/stockport-county-possess-2020-vision-8776335| title=Stockport County possess 2020 vision| work=Manchester Evening News |accessdate=12 August 2015|last=Browne|first=Gavin|date=5 March 2015}}</ref> This document focused on four key points- stability, sustainability, stadium and success.<ref name=\"Moving Forward\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304112916/https://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/moving-forward-2301850.aspx| title=Moving Forward| work=stockportcounty.com  | accessdate=13 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/moving-forward-2301850.aspx|archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Moving Forward Document\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924110549/http://www.stockportcounty.com/documents/stockport-county-moving-forward43-2301849.pdf| title=Moving Forward Document| work=stockportcounty.com  | accessdate=13 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://www.stockportcounty.com/documents/stockport-county-moving-forward43-2301849.pdf|archivedate=24 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nSummer of 2015 saw Stockport starting their third season at National League North level, Neil Young was named as Stockport's new permanent manager after having previous successes in the same division with other clubs.<ref name=\"Neil Young named new manager of Stockport County\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924110818/http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/neil-young-named-new-manager-of-stockport-county-2459326.aspx| title=Neil Young named new manager of Stockport County| work=stockportcounty.com  | accessdate=12 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/neil-young-named-new-manager-of-stockport-county-2459326.aspx|archivedate=16 May 2015 }}</ref> However, the optimism around Young's appointment soon dissipated; after failing to mount a serious promotion challenge, Young departed in January 2016 after a run of one win in 12 matches.<ref name=\"Chester FC: Neil Young resigns as Stockport County manager\">{{cite web |last1=Green |first1=Jim |url= https://www.cheshire-live.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/chester-fc-neil-young-resigns-10725399| title= Chester FC: Neil Young resigns as Stockport County manager |date=13 January 2016 | publisher=cheshire-live.co.uk | accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref>The club once again turned to [[Jim Gannon]], who returned for a third stint as manager after a successful period at [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]]. <ref>{{cite news |last1=Byrne |first1=Sam |title=Jim Gannon returns to Stockport County for third stint as manager |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/jim-gannon-returns-stockport-county-10754650 |website=Manchester Evening News |date=18 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 2015\u201316 season Gannon helped the club to a 9th-place finish<ref name=\"National League North Table 2015/16\">{{cite web | url=https://www.thenationalleague.org.uk/archive4088-match-info/tables?table_id=d-18375| title= National League North Table 2015/16 |publisher= National League |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 25 April 2016 }}</ref>and a victory in the [[Cheshire Senior Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Harrison |first1=Paul |title=Stockport County crowned Cheshire Cup champions |url=https://southmanchesternews.co.uk/stockport-county-crowned-cheshire-cup-champions/ |website=South Manchester News |date=27 April 2016}}</ref>\nThe following campaign in 2016/17, Gannon rebuilt his squad and flirted with the playoffs for much of the season, before eventually finishing eighth, just one point off securing a playoff position.<ref name=\"National League North Table 2016/17\">{{cite web | url=https://www.thenationalleague.org.uk/archive5398-match-info/tables?table_id=d-26693| title= National League North Table 2016/17 |publisher= National League |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 24 April 2017 }}</ref>The club's top scorer [[Danny Lloyd (footballer)|Danny Lloyd]], who had signed the previous summer, left at the end of the season to join County's former League One rivals, and Gannon's former club, [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Coney |first1=Steven|title=Highly-rated Stockport winger Danny Lloyd becomes latest Non-League star to join Peterborough |url=https://www.thenonleaguefootballpaper.com/latest-news/conference-premier/19141/highly-rated-stockport-winger-danny-lloyd-becomes-latest-non-league-star-to-join-peterborough |website=The Non League Football Paper |date=9 May 2017}}</ref>\nThe progress under Gannon continued in the 2017\u201318 season \u2013 the first time the same manager had been in charge for the start of two successive seasons since 2008 \u2013 as Stockport finished the season in fifth place and reached the playoffs.<ref name=\"National League North Table 2017/18\">{{cite web | url=https://www.thenationalleague.org.uk/archive6517-match-info/tables?table_id=d-35404| title= National League North Table 2017/18 |publisher= National League |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 24 April 2018 }}</ref>\n[[File:CountyNLNWinners3.jpg|250px|thumb|County Manager [[Jim Gannon]] (right) lifts the National League North trophy alongside [[Ash Palmer]] (left) & Club Captain [[Paul Turnbull]] (centre)]][[File:Stockport County win National League North - Commentary.ogg|300px|thumb|Commentary of the final moments of Stockport County's victory over Nuneaton Borough to secure their first league title in 52 years.]]\nHowever, Stockport lost 1\u20130 at the quarter-final stage to [[Chorley F.C.|Chorley]] at [[Edgeley Park]] in front of a crowd of 6,230.<ref name=\"Play-Off Report & Pics: County 0-1 Chorley\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/play-off-report-pics-county-0-1-chorley/| title= Play-Off Report & Pics: County 0\u20131 Chorley |publisher= stockportcounty.com |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 2 May 2018 }}</ref> Following the end of the season, the club's top scorer for that campaign, [[Jason Oswell]] left to join [[Morecambe F.C.]].<ref name=\"Jason Oswell: Morecambe sign striker from non-league Stockport County\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44635030| title= Jason Oswell: Morecambe sign striker from non-league Stockport County| publisher= BBC Sport |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 27 June 2018 }}</ref>However, after coming close to promotion in the previous campaign, 2018\u201319 was a much happier one. After a slow start, Stockport reached the 2nd round of the [[FA Cup]], beating [[League Two]] side [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] 3\u20131 at Huish Park in round one, <ref name=\"Emirates FA Cup Report & Pics: Yeovil Town 1-3 County\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/fa-cup-report-pics-yeovil-town-1-3-county/| title= Emirates FA Cup Report & Pics: Yeovil Town 1\u20133 County |publisher= stockportcounty.com |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 10 November 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"THE FA CUP - FIRST ROUND Yeovil 1-3 Stockport County\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46080956| title= THE FA CUP \u2013 FIRST ROUND Yeovil 1\u20133 Stockport County| publisher= BBC Sport |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 10 November 2018 }}</ref> before eventually losing to [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] at [[The Hive Stadium|The Hive]] in early December.<ref name=\"FA Cup Report & Pics: Barnet 1-0 County\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/fa-cup-report-pics-barnet-1-0-county/| title= FA Cup Report & Pics: Barnet 1\u20130 County |publisher= stockportcounty.com |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 2 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McLoughlin |first1=Ciaran |title=Bees secure third round spot after narrow victory over Stockport County at the Hive |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2018/dec/02/barnet-stockport-county-report-021218 |website=The Football Association |date=2 December 2018}}</ref> \nStockport then went on a 23-match unbeaten run in all competitions (equalling a club record), which was ended with a 1\u20130 defeat away to [[Brackley Town]]<ref name=\"Report & Pics: Brackley Town 1-0 County\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/report-pics-brackley-town-1-0-county/| title= Report & Pics: Brackley Town 1\u20130 County |publisher= stockportcounty.com |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 9 March 2019}}</ref> and also reached the [[FA Trophy]] Semi-Finals for the first time, losing 3\u20132 on aggregate to National League high-flyers [[AFC Fylde]] after two fiercely fought matches. <ref name=\"FA Trophy Report & Pics: AFC Fylde 0-0 County\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/fa-trophy-report-pics-afc-fylde-0-0-county/| title= FA Trophy Report & Pics: AFC Fylde 0\u20130 County |publisher= stockportcounty.com |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 16 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"FA Trophy Report & Pics: County 2-3 AFC Fylde\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/fa-trophy-report-pics-county-2-3-afc-fylde/| title= FA Trophy Report & Pics: County 2\u20133 AFC Fylde |publisher= stockportcounty.com |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 23 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"FA Trophy: AFC Fylde win at Stockport & Leyton Orient beat Telford to reach final\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47674083| title= FA Trophy: AFC Fylde win at Stockport & Leyton Orient beat Telford to reach final| publisher= BBC Sport |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 23 March 2019}}</ref> After a strong end to the campaign, Stockport found themselves in the hunt for the title. On the final day of the campaign, the Hatters won 3\u20130 at [[Nuneaton Borough F.C.|Nuneaton Borough]] to clinch their first league title in 52 years, and with it claim promotion back to the National League.<ref name=\"Report & Pics: Nuneaton Borough 0-3 County\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/report-pics-nuneaton-borough-0-3-county/| title= Report & Pics: Nuneaton Borough 0\u20133 County |publisher= stockportcounty.com |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 28 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"WE ARE CHAMPIONS!\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/we-are-champions/| title= WE ARE CHAMPIONS! |publisher= stockportcounty.com |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Swettenham |first1=Lee |title=Thousands celebrate as Stockport County win first league title in 52 years |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/stockport-county-champions-promoted-fans-16192266 |website=Manchester Evening News |date=28 April 2019}}</ref> As with the previous two campaigns; top scorer for the 2018/19 season, [[Matty Warburton]] left the club at the end of the campaign after two years, joining [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]]. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Willsher |first1=Gareth |title=Matt Warburton Ready For Challenge of Joining Northampton Town |url=https://www.ntfc.co.uk/news/2019/may/warburton_ready_challenge/ |website=Northampton Town Football Club |date=9 May 2019}}</ref>\nHowever, the club started life back in national-level football for the first time in six years well; Stockport finished the decade in the [[National League (division)|National League]] playoff positions.<ref name=\"AFC Fylde 1-2 Stockport County\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50875757| title= AFC Fylde 1\u20132 Stockport County| publisher= BBC Sport |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |date= 28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020 \u2013 present: Return to National Football===\n\nWith the club competing once again in the [[National League (division)|National League]] under [[Jim Gannon]]'s guidance, in January 2020, local businessman Mark Stott purchased County for an undisclosed sum, making the club debt-free in the process; Stott pledged to return the club to full-time football, help to climb back up the [[English Football League|Football League]] and find a new training ground for County.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stockport County FC, which currently competes in the Vanarama National League, are pleased to confirm the sale of the Club to local businessman, Mark Stott. |date=17 January 2020|url=https://www.stockportcounty.com/club-statement-2/}}</ref>\n\n==Colours, crests and traditions==\nStockport County's traditional kit colours are blue and white, although they have played in other colours throughout their history. Originally competing in blue and white striped jerseys and white shorts, they experimented with red and white stripes in the early 1900s, and from the mid-1930s to mid-1960s played in white jerseys and black shorts.<ref name=\"Our History\" /><ref name=\"Kit History\">{{cite web | url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Stockport_County/Stockport_County.htm#KitHistory | title=Kit History | publisher=historicalkits.co.uk | accessdate=8 September 2013|last=Moor|first=Dave|date=8 September 2013}}</ref> No set pattern has been established for the club's use of blue and white as main colours, as they have played at various times in a white jersey with a blue band and blue shorts and a blue jersey with white pin stripes and white shorts. They made a short experiment with an [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]-style kit, light blue and white stripes with black shorts, after the [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978 World Cup]]. This was abandoned after the outbreak of the [[Falklands War]],<ref name=\"Background\" /> and the club returned to blue and white striped tops with blue shorts in the 1980s. Stockport marked their 125th anniversary during 2008 by bringing in a third kit \u2013 a gold colour with black trim.<ref name=\"Coca Cola League Two 2007 - 2008 Kits\">{{cite web | url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/English_Football_League/season/2007-2008/league-two.html#stockport| title=Coca Cola League Two 2007 \u2013 2008 | work=Historical Kits | accessdate=9 September 2013|last=Moor|first=Dave|date=9 September 2013}}</ref> The kit was worn on 17 occasions, all away trips. The strip was retired 'undefeated' at the end of the year, having been worn for 13 victories and 4 draws.<ref name=\"Express Lines - Magic Gold\">{{cite journal |last=Smeadley |first=Simon |date=16 September 2008|title=Express Lines \u2013 Magic Gold |journal=Stockport County Match Programme Vs. Northampton Town |page=21 |location= Stockport}}</ref> The kit was also worn during a match against [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] which was abandoned after 59 minutes.<ref name=\"Chester 'Abandoned' City\">{{cite journal |last=Smeadley |first=Simon |date=5 April 2008|title=Chester 'Abandoned' City |journal=Stockport County Match Programme Vs. Darlington |page=31 |location= Stockport}}</ref>\n\nThe club crest, which was used for many years until 2010 when the club exited administration, was based on the achievement of arms of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Stockport]]. It was altered in 2006 to resemble the town's arms more closely, including the [[Latin]] motto ''Animo et Fide'', which loosely translated, means ''With Courage and Faith''.<ref name=\"Stockport - Explanation of the Arms of Stockport\">{{cite web | url=http://www.manchester2002-uk.com/towns/stockport3.html | title=Stockport \u2013 Explanation of the Arms of Stockport | publisher=manchester2002-uk.com | accessdate=29 August 2015 | last=Moss | first=John | date=28 April 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122022349/http://www.manchester2002-uk.com/towns/stockport3.html | archive-date=22 November 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The blue shield is taken from the coat of arms of the 'de Stokeport' family, from whom Stockport derives its name.<ref name=\"Stockport - Explanation of the Arms of Stockport\" /><ref name=\"Secret Stockport\" /> The twin-towered castle above the shield is [[Stockport Castle]], which stood until 1775.<ref name=\"STOCKPORT CASTLE\">{{PastScape|mnumber=1085399 | mname=STOCKPORT CASTLE | accessdate=29 August 2015|date=29 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter the completion by the 2015 Group takeover of the club, a new crest was adopted. It was still based on the [[Stockport]] coat of arms, though the ''Animo et Fide'' motto was removed, along with a patch of green at the base of the badge; the [[flag of Cheshire]], featuring a sword and three wheatsheaves, replaced the golden lozenges and crosslets in the shield. The medals hanging from the lion's rampant (which represented Cheshire and [[Lancashire]], owing to Stockport's location astride the Mersey which forms the historic border between the two counties) were removed. It also saw the return of a football on the shield. This change was made in part because as of the 2010\u201311 season, Stockport County was sponsored by the Metropolitan Borough Council.<ref name=\"Npower League Two 2010 - 2011 Kits\">{{cite web | url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/English_Football_League/season/2010-2011/league-two.html| title=Npower League Two 2010 \u2013 2011| work=Historical Kits | accessdate=9 September 2013|last=Moor|first=Dave|date=9 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe crest was altered in 2011 to re-include the town motto. The new version added two white ribbons \u2013 one at the top, with ''Animo et Fide'', and one at the bottom with ''Stockport County F.C.''. In addition, the football was again removed from the shield. The [[Stockport County Supporters' Co - Operative]] used the blue on white cross symbol from the 1978 badge as the main identifier in their company logo. Stockport's kit was supplied by local manufacturer [[Umbro]] who supplied all three kits for the 2013\u201314 season, replacing [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], thus making Stockport the only senior club in the UK to wear the Umbro strip in the 2013\u201314 season.<ref name=\"Background\" /><ref name=\"New Kit Deal Agreed\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103202405/http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-05-09-new-kit-deal-815995.aspx| title=New Kit Deal Agreed| work=stockportcounty.com  | accessdate=13 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-05-09-new-kit-deal-815995.aspx |archivedate=8 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\nFrom the start of the 2014\u201315 season, Stockport again changed their kit manufacturer, this time from Umbro to Spanish-based manufacturer [[Joma|Joma,]] who supplied a new Home, Away and Third kit along with training wear.<ref name=\"County hope they're dressed for success\">{{cite web | url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/stockport-county-new-kits-sponsors-7434069 | title= County hope they're dressed for success |accessdate=16 September 2014 |date=26 July 2014 |last=Browne|first=Gavin|location=Manchester|work=Manchester Evening News}}</ref><ref name=\"Robinsons sponsor new alternate away strip\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303225928/http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2014-07-09-robinsons-1730439.aspx| title=Robinsons sponsor new alternate away strip| work=stockportcounty.com  | accessdate=13 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2014-07-09-robinsons-1730439.aspx |archivedate=11 July 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"Kit deal sees County go back to the future\">{{cite web | url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/stockport-county-robinsons-shirt-sponsorship-7395521  | title= Kit deal sees County go back to the future | publisher=Manchester Evening News | date=9 July 2014 | accessdate=22 July 2015 |last=Browne|first=Gavin}}</ref>\n\n===Kit manufacturers and main shirt sponsors===\n<ref name=\"Kit History\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Period\n!Kit manufacturer\n!Shirt sponsor\n|-\n|1976\u20131979\n|rowspan=1|[[Bukta]]\n|rowspan=4|''none''\n|-\n|1978\u20131979\n|rowspan=1|[[Admiral (sportswear)|Admiral]]\n|-\n|1979\u20131984\n|rowspan=1|[[Adidas]]\n|-\n\n|1984\u20131985\n|rowspan=2|[[Bukta]]\n|-\n|1985\u20131986\n|rowspan=1|Langdale Services\n|-\n|1986\u20131987\n|rowspan=1|[[Umbro]]\n|rowspan=1|''None''\n|-\n|1987\u20131989\n|rowspan=1|En-S\n|rowspan=1|Messenger Newspapers\n|-\n|1989\u20131991\n|rowspan=2|Ribero\n|rowspan=1|Sovereign Rubber\n|-\n|1990\u20131991\n|rowspan=1|Gordon Ford Group\n|-\n|1991\u20131993\n|rowspan=1|[[Gola (manufacturer)|Gola]]\n|rowspan=1|[[Cobra Beer|Cobra]]\n|-\n|1993\u20131995\n|rowspan=1|Super League\n|rowspan=4|[[Robinsons Brewery|Robinsons Best Bitter]]\n|-\n|1995\u20131996\n|rowspan=1|M\n|-\n|1996\u20131999\n|rowspan=1|[[Adidas]]\n|-\n|1999\u20132002\n|rowspan=1|Patrick\n|-\n|2002\u20132007\n|rowspan=1|TFG Sports\n|rowspan=1|Scandia<ref name=\"We're not bitter\">{{cite web | url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/other-sport/were-not-bitter-1176122 | title=We're not bitter | work=Manchester Evening News | date= 4 September 2007 | accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|2007\u20132009\n|rowspan=1|[[Diadora]]<ref name=\"County Kit Sponsors Diadora Go Bust\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090921131408/https://stockport.vitalfootball.co.uk/article.asp?a=160860| title=County Kit Sponsors Diadora Go Bust| work=Stockport Vital Football  | accessdate=13 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://stockport.vitalfootball.co.uk/article.asp?a=160860 |archivedate=10 July 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Stockport County new 07/08 diadora home football kit\">{{cite web | url=http://www.footballshirtculture.com/07/08-Kits/stockport-county-new-0708-diadora-home-football-kit.html   | title=Stockport County new 07/08 diadora home football kit | work=footballshirtculture.com | date=1 August 2007 | accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n|rowspan=2|Just Search<ref name=\"Stockport County new 07/08 diadora home football kit\" /><ref name=\"New County kit unveiled\" />\n|-\n|2009\u20132010\n|rowspan=1|[[Macron (sportswear)|Macron]]<ref name=\"New County kit unveiled\">{{cite web | url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/new-county-kit-unveiled-925027 | title=New County kit unveiled | work=Manchester Evening News | date=22 July 2009 | accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|2010\u20132011\n|rowspan=3|[[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n|rowspan=1|[[Stockport Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n|-\n|2010\u20132012\n|rowspan=1|GT Law\n|-\n|2012\u20132013\n|rowspan=1|GT Law ''(Home and Away)''<br />Leemic ''(Third)''\n|-\n|2013\u20132014\n|rowspan=1|[[Umbro]]<ref name=\"New Kit Deal Agreed\" />\n|rowspan=1|Stockport Sports Village ''(Home)''<ref name=\"Home Shirt Sponsor Unveiled\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924110644/http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/2013-06-21-home-shirt-sponsor-875154.aspx| tit